{"title_page": "Forfar Infirmary", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Forfar Infirmary\n| Org/Group  = [[NHS Tayside]]\n| Image      = Forfar Infirmary - geograph.org.uk - 113492.jpg\n| Caption    = Forfar Infirmary\n| Logo       = \n| Logo Size  = \n| Location   =  Arbroath Road, [[Forfar]]\n| Region     = \n| State      = \n| Country    = Scotland\n| HealthCare = [[NHS Scotland]]\n| Type       = General\n| Speciality = \n| Standards  = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency  = \n| Affiliation= \n| Beds       = \n| Founded    = 1862\n| Closed     = 2005\n| Website    = \n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| Coordinates = {{coord|56.6455|-2.8760|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type=Scotland Angus\n |map_caption=Shown in Angus\n|}}\n\n'''Forfar Infirmary''' was a health facility in Arbroath Road in [[Forfar]], [[Angus, Scotland|Angus]], Scotland. It was managed by [[NHS Tayside]].\n\n==History==\nThe facility had its origins in the Forfar Poorhouse which was completed in June 1861.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.workhouses.org.uk/Forfar/|title=Forfar|publisher=Workhouses|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> The infirmary, which was designed to serve the local community as well as the poorhouse, opened on a nearby site in July 1862.<ref name=hh>{{cite web|url=https://historic-hospitals.com/gazetteer/angus/|title=Forfar Infirmary|publisher=Historic Hospitals|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://online.aberdeenshire.gov.uk/smrpub/master/detail.aspx?tab=main&refno=NO45SE0190|title=Forfar Infirmary|publisher=Aberdeenshire Council|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> Two wings were added in 1922 and a nurses' home was built in 1927 before it joined the [[National Health Service]] in 1948.<ref name=hh/> After services had transferred to [[Whitehills Hospital]], Forfar Infirmary closed in 2005 and the buildings were subsequently demolished.<ref name=hh/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/287795/forfar-arbroath-road-forfar-infirmary|title=Forfar Infirmary|publisher=Canmore|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in Angus]]\n[[Category:Defunct hospitals in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1862]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1862]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:NHS Tayside]]\n[[Category:Forfar]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Forfar Infirmary\n| Org/Group  = [[NHS Tayside]]\n| Image      = Forfar Infirmary - geograph.org.uk - 113492.jpg\n| Caption    = Forfar Infirmary\n| Logo       = \n| Logo Size  = \n| Location   =  Arbroath Road, [[Forfar]]\n| Region     = \n| State      = \n| Country    = Scotland\n| HealthCare = [[NHS Scotland]]\n| Type       = General\n| Speciality = \n| Standards  = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency  = \n| Affiliation= \n| Beds       = \n| Founded    = 1862\n| Closed     = 2005\n| Website    = \n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| Coordinates = {{coord|56.6455|-2.8760|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type=Scotland Angus\n |map_caption=Shown in Angus\n|}}\n\n'''Forfar Infirmary''' was a health facility in Arbroath Road in [[Forfar]], [[Angus, Scotland|Angus]], Scotland. It was managed by [[NHS Tayside]].\n\n==History==\nThe facility had its origins in the Forfar Poorhouse which was completed in June 1861.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.workhouses.org.uk/Forfar/|title=Forfar|publisher=Workhouses|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> The infirmary, which was designed to serve the local community as well as the poorhouse, opened on a nearby site in July 1862.<ref name=hh>{{cite web|url=https://historic-hospitals.com/gazetteer/angus/|title=Forfar Infirmary|publisher=Historic Hospitals|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://online.aberdeenshire.gov.uk/smrpub/master/detail.aspx?tab=main&refno=NO45SE0190|title=Forfar Infirmary|publisher=Aberdeenshire Council|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> Two wings were added in 1922 and a nurses' home was built in 1927 before it joined the [[National Health Service]] in 1948.<ref name=hh/> After services had transferred to [[Whitehills Hospital]], Forfar Infirmary closed in 2005 and the buildings were subsequently demolished.<ref name=hh/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/287795/forfar-arbroath-road-forfar-infirmary|title=Forfar Infirmary|publisher=Canmore|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in Angus]]\n[[Category:Defunct hospitals in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1862]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1862]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Scotland]]\n[[Category:NHS Tayside]]\n[[Category:Forfar]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forfar_Infirmary"}
{"title_page": "Reedham railway station (Norfolk)", "text_new": "{{use British English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n| symbol       = rail\n| image_name   = Rail-reedhamstation-amoswolfe.jpg\n| caption      = Reedham railway station in 2001, looking towards Reedham Junction\n| name         = Reedham\n| manager      = [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]\n| code         = REE\n| locale       = [[Reedham, Norfolk|Reedham]]\n| borough      = [[Broadland]], [[Norfolk]]\n<!-- | lowusage0506 = {{decrease}} 21,127\n| lowusage0405 = {{increase}} 23,832\n| lowusage0607 = {{increase}} 24,173\n| lowusage0708 = {{increase}} 36,889\n| lowusage0809 = {{decrease}} 36,552\n| lowusage0910 = {{decrease}} 35,294\n| lowusage1011 = {{increase}} 40,326\n| lowusage1112 = {{increase}} 43,870\n| lowusage1213 = {{increase}} 46,112\n| lowusage1314 = {{decrease}} 45,482-->\n| lowusage1415 = {{decrease}} 45,336\n| lowusage1516 = {{decrease}} 43,080\n| lowusage1617 = {{increase}} 50,302\n| lowusage1718 = {{decrease}} 46,020\n| lowusage1819 = {{decrease}} 45,618\n| platforms    = 2\n| gridref      = TG413022\n| original     = [[Yarmouth and Norwich Railway]]<ref name=\"Butt\">{{Butt-Stations|page=196}}</ref><br>[[Eastern Counties Railway]]\n| pregroup     = [[Great Eastern Railway]]\n| postgroup    = [[London and North Eastern Railway]]\n| years1       = 1 May 1844\n| events1      = Opened as ''Reedham''<ref name=\"Butt\"/>\n| years2       = 1 June 1904\n| events2      = Replaced by new station {{circa}} 300 m west<ref name=\"Butt\"/>\n| years3       = 1928\n| events3      = Renamed ''Reedham (Norfolk)''<ref name=\"Butt\"/>\n| dft_category = F1\n}}\n\n'''Reedham railway station''' is on the [[Wherry Lines]] in the [[East of England]], serving the village of [[Reedham, Norfolk]]. It is {{convert|12|mi|13|chain|km}} down the line from {{rws|Norwich}} and is situated between {{rws|Cantley}} to the west and, to the east, {{rws|Berney Arms}} on the {{rws|Great Yarmouth}} branch or {{rws|Haddiscoe}} on the {{rws|Lowestoft}} branch.<ref>Ordnance Survey (2005). ''OS Explorer Map OL40 - The Broads''. {{ISBN|0-319-23769-9}}.</ref> It is commonly suffixed as '''Reedham (Norfolk)''' in order to distinguish it from the [[Reedham (Surrey) railway station|station of the same name in Surrey]]. Its three-letter station code is REE.\n\nThe station is currently managed by [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]], which also operates all trains serving the station. The majority of services run between Norwich and Lowestoft, but three trains per day run to and from Great Yarmouth via the remote [[Berney Arms railway station|Berney Arms station]]. Services are operated by the brand new [[Stadler FLIRT]] [[British Rail Class 755|Class 755]] [[Electro-diesel multiple unit|bi-mode]] multiple units, which entered service on the Wherry Lines in autumn 2019.\n\n==History==\n\nThe Bill for the [[Yarmouth & Norwich Railway]] (Y&NR) received Royal Assent on 18 June 1842. Work started on the line in April 1843 and the line and its stations were opened on 1 May 1844. Reedham station opened with the line and was, as it is now, situated east of Cantley station and west of Berney Arms station. The Y&NR was the first public railway line in Norfolk.\nOn 30 June 1845 a Bill authorising the amalgamation of the Y&NR with the [[Norwich & Brandon Railway]] came into effect and Reedham station became a Norfolk Railway asset.<ref name=Butt /><ref>C.J. Allen {{Full citation needed|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1845 an Act incorporated the Lowestoft Railway & Harbour Company (LR&HC). In 1846 the LR&HC was leased to the Norfolk Railway (NR) and work started on building a line from Lowestoft, in Suffolk to join the Yarmouth & Norwich line South-East of Reedham. On 1 July 1847 the NR opens the Lowestoft to Reedham line. The station south-east of Reedham on the line to Lowestoft was Haddiscoe.\n\nA couple of months after the Lowestoft line opened, the next station west, {{rws|Cantley}}, was closed by the Norfolk Railway.\n\nThe [[Eastern Counties Railway]] (ECR) and its rival the [[Eastern Union Railway]] (EUR) were both sizing up the NR to acquire and expand their railway empire. The ECR trumped the EUR by taking over the NR, including Reedham Station on 8 May 1848.\n\nThe ECR reopened Cantley in 1851, once again making it the next station west.\n\nBy the 1860s the railways in East Anglia were in financial trouble, and most were leased to the Eastern Counties Railway, which wished to amalgamate formally but could not obtain government agreement for this until an Act of Parliament on 7 August 1862, when the [[Great Eastern Railway]] (GER) was formed by the amalgamation. Actually, Reedham became a GER station on 1 July 1862 when the GER took over the ECR and the EUR before the Bill received the Royal Assent.<ref>CJ Allen - Great Eastern - page46</ref>\n\nBy the first decade of the last Century the GER started building new stations at Reedham and at Haddiscoe. On 9 May 1904 Haddiscoe Station was closed and replaced by Haddiscoe Low Level on a new site. On 1 June 1904 the GER opened today's Reedham Station and closed the Y&NR station which was 300 metres East of the new station.\n\nThe system settled down for the next 17 years, apart from the disruption of the [[World War I|First World War]]. The difficult economic circumstances that existed after the war led the Government to pass the [[Railways Act 1921]], which led to the creation of the [[Big Four (British railway companies)|Big Four]]. The GER amalgamated with several other companies to form the [[London and North Eastern Railway]] (LNER). Reedham became a LNER station on 1 January 1923.\n\nIn 1928 the LNER renamed Reedham as ''Reedham (Norfolk)'' to distinguish it from the [[Southern Railway (UK)|Southern Railway)]] station of [[Reedham (Surrey) railway station|Reedham-Surrey]].\n\nAt [[Transport Act 1947|nationalisation]] in 1948, the station and its services were transferred to the [[Eastern Region of British Railways]].\n\nFollowing the [[privatisation of British Rail]], [[Railtrack]] became responsible for infrastructure maintenance in 1994. Following Railtrack's financial problems [[Network Rail]] took over operation of the infrastructure in 2002.\n\nThe station and its operations came under the [[Anglia Railways]] franchise in 1997. Subsequently, [[National Express East Anglia]], then known as ''One'', took over management in 2004.\n\nThe station, along with its services, were transferred to [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Abellio Greater Anglia]] in 2012.\n\nIn October 2018, Network Rail remodelled the Reedham Junction layout and begun the resignalling process, temporarily closing the Berney Arms line to Great Yarmouth. It reopened on 24 February 2020.\n\n==Services==\nAs of April 2020 the typical Monday - Friday daytime off-peak service at Reedham is as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable vatop\"\n! Operator\n! Route\n! Rolling stock\n! Typical frequency\n|-\n| [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]\n| {{rws|Norwich}} - {{rws|Brundall}} - {{rws|Cantley}} - Reedham - {{rws|Haddiscoe}} - {{rws|Somerleyton}} - {{rws|Oulton Broad North}} - {{rws|Lowestoft}}\n| [[British Rail Class 755|Class 755]]\n| One train every two hours\n|-\n| [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]\n| {{rws|Norwich}} - {{rws|Brundall}} - {{rws|Cantley}} - Reedham - {{rws|Berney Arms}} (request stop) - {{rws|Great Yarmouth}}\n| [[British Rail Class 755|Class 755]]\n| Two trains a day in both directions\n|}\n\nOn Saturdays between February and May there is an additional train in both directions between Norwich and Great Yarmouth via Reedham, calling at Brundall and Reedham only. The ''down'' service (towards Yarmouth) departs Norwich at 05:32 and the ''up'' service (towards Norwich) departs Great Yarmouth at 23:34. <ref>https://www.greateranglia.co.uk/sites/default/files/assets/download_ct/20191115/g3QuBXav3gNQvCuLrppp2rT2evmhcVRQ97fVGWRUlWk/ga1912_table_8_web.pdf</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Reedham (Norfolk) railway station}}\n{{stn art lnk|REE|NR133EZ}}\n\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line one to two|previous=[[Cantley railway station|Cantley]]|next1=[[Berney Arms railway station|Berney Arms]]|next2=[[Haddiscoe railway station|Haddiscoe]]|route1=[[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]<br><small>[[Wherry Lines]]<br>Great Yarmouth branch</small>|route2=[[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]<br><small>[[Wherry Lines]]<br>Lowestoft branch</small>|col={{NXEA colour}}}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{coord|52.565|N|1.560|E|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Norfolk]]\n[[Category:Former Great Eastern Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Greater Anglia franchise railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1844]]\n", "text_old": "{{use British English|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox GB station\n| symbol       = rail\n| image_name   = Rail-reedhamstation-amoswolfe.jpg\n| caption      = Reedham railway station in 2001, looking towards Reedham Junction\n| name         = Reedham\n| manager      = [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]\n| code         = REE\n| locale       = [[Reedham, Norfolk|Reedham]]\n| borough      = [[Broadland]], [[Norfolk]]\n<!-- | lowusage0506 = {{decrease}} 21,127\n| lowusage0405 = {{increase}} 23,832\n| lowusage0607 = {{increase}} 24,173\n| lowusage0708 = {{increase}} 36,889\n| lowusage0809 = {{decrease}} 36,552\n| lowusage0910 = {{decrease}} 35,294\n| lowusage1011 = {{increase}} 40,326\n| lowusage1112 = {{increase}} 43,870\n| lowusage1213 = {{increase}} 46,112\n| lowusage1314 = {{decrease}} 45,482-->\n| lowusage1415 = {{decrease}} 45,336\n| lowusage1516 = {{decrease}} 43,080\n| lowusage1617 = {{increase}} 50,302\n| lowusage1718 = {{decrease}} 46,020\n| lowusage1819 = {{decrease}} 45,618\n| platforms    = 2\n| gridref      = TG413022\n| original     = [[Yarmouth and Norwich Railway]]<ref name=\"Butt\">{{Butt-Stations|page=196}}</ref><br>[[Eastern Counties Railway]]\n| pregroup     = [[Great Eastern Railway]]\n| postgroup    = [[London and North Eastern Railway]]\n| years1       = 1 May 1844\n| events1      = Opened as ''Reedham''<ref name=\"Butt\"/>\n| years2       = 1 June 1904\n| events2      = Replaced by new station {{circa}} 300 m west<ref name=\"Butt\"/>\n| years3       = 1928\n| events3      = Renamed ''Reedham (Norfolk)''<ref name=\"Butt\"/>\n| dft_category = F1\n}}\n\n'''Reedham railway station''' is on the [[Wherry Lines]] in the [[East of England]], serving the village of [[Reedham, Norfolk]]. It is {{convert|12|mi|13|chain|km}} down the line from {{rws|Norwich}} and is situated between {{rws|Cantley}} to the west and, to the east, {{rws|Berney Arms}} on the {{rws|Great Yarmouth}} branch or {{rws|Haddiscoe}} on the {{rws|Lowestoft}} branch.<ref>Ordnance Survey (2005). ''OS Explorer Map OL40 - The Broads''. {{ISBN|0-319-23769-9}}.</ref> It is commonly suffixed as '''Reedham (Norfolk)''' in order to distinguish it from the [[Reedham (Surrey) railway station|station of the same name in Surrey]]. Its three-letter station code is REE.\n\nThe station is currently managed by [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]], which also operates all trains serving the station. The majority of services run between Norwich and Lowestoft, but three trains per day run to and from Great Yarmouth via the remote [[Berney Arms railway station|Berney Arms station]]. Services are operated by the brand new [[Stadler FLIRT]] [[British Rail Class 755|Class 755]] [[Electro-diesel multiple unit|bi-mode]] multiple units, which entered service on the Wherry Lines in autumn 2019.\n\n==History==\n\nThe Bill for the [[Yarmouth & Norwich Railway]] (Y&NR) received Royal Assent on 18 June 1842. Work started on the line in April 1843 and the line and its stations were opened on 1 May 1844. Reedham station opened with the line and was, as it is now, situated east of Cantley station and west of Berney Arms station. The Y&NR was the first public railway line in Norfolk.\nOn 30 June 1845 a Bill authorising the amalgamation of the Y&NR with the [[Norwich & Brandon Railway]] came into effect and Reedham station became a Norfolk Railway asset.<ref name=Butt /><ref>C.J. Allen {{Full citation needed|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1845 an Act incorporated the Lowestoft Railway & Harbour Company (LR&HC). In 1846 the LR&HC was leased to the Norfolk Railway (NR) and work started on building a line from Lowestoft, in Suffolk to join the Yarmouth & Norwich line South-East of Reedham. On 1 July 1847 the NR opens the Lowestoft to Reedham line. The station south-east of Reedham on the line to Lowestoft was Haddiscoe.\n\nA couple of months after the Lowestoft line opened, the next station west, {{rws|Cantley}}, was closed by the Norfolk Railway.\n\nThe [[Eastern Counties Railway]] (ECR) and its rival the [[Eastern Union Railway]] (EUR) were both sizing up the NR to acquire and expand their railway empire. The ECR trumped the EUR by taking over the NR, including Reedham Station on 8 May 1848.\n\nThe ECR reopened Cantley in 1851, once again making it the next station west.\n\nBy the 1860s the railways in East Anglia were in financial trouble, and most were leased to the Eastern Counties Railway, which wished to amalgamate formally but could not obtain government agreement for this until an Act of Parliament on 7 August 1862, when the [[Great Eastern Railway]] (GER) was formed by the amalgamation. Actually, Reedham became a GER station on 1 July 1862 when the GER took over the ECR and the EUR before the Bill received the Royal Assent.<ref>CJ Allen - Great Eastern - page46</ref>\n\nBy the first decade of the last Century the GER started building new stations at Reedham and at Haddiscoe. On 9 May 1904 Haddiscoe Station was closed and replaced by Haddiscoe Low Level on a new site. On 1 June 1904 the GER opened today's Reedham Station and closed the Y&NR station which was 300 metres East of the new station.\n\nThe system settled down for the next 17 years, apart from the disruption of the [[World War I|First World War]]. The difficult economic circumstances that existed after the war led the Government to pass the [[Railways Act 1921]], which led to the creation of the [[Big Four (British railway companies)|Big Four]]. The GER amalgamated with several other companies to form the [[London and North Eastern Railway]] (LNER). Reedham became a LNER station on 1 January 1923.\n\nIn 1928 the LNER renamed Reedham as ''Reedham (Norfolk)'' to distinguish it from the [[Southern Railway (UK)|Southern Railway)]] station of [[Reedham (Surrey) railway station|Reedham-Surrey]].\n\nAt [[Transport Act 1947|nationalisation]] in 1948, the station and its services were transferred to the [[Eastern Region of British Railways]].\n\nFollowing the [[privatisation of British Rail]], [[Railtrack]] became responsible for infrastructure maintenance in 1994. Following Railtrack's financial problems [[Network Rail]] took over operation of the infrastructure in 2002.\n\nThe station and its operations came under the [[Anglia Railways]] franchise in 1997. Subsequently, [[National Express East Anglia]], then known as ''One'', took over management in 2004.\n\nThe station, along with its services, were transferred to [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Abellio Greater Anglia]] in 2012.\n\nIn October 2018, Network Rail remodelled the Reedham Junction layout and begun the resignalling process, temporarily closing the Berney Arms line to Great Yarmouth. It reopened on 24 February 2020.\n\n==Services==\nAs of April 2020 the typical Monday-Friday daytime off-peak service at Reedham is as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable vatop\"\n! Operator\n! Route\n! Rolling stock\n! Typical frequency\n|-\n| [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]\n| {{rws|Norwich}} - {{rws|Brundall}} - {{rws|Cantley}} - Reedham - {{rws|Haddiscoe}} - {{rws|Somerleyton}} - {{rws|Oulton Broad North}} - {{rws|Lowestoft}}\n| [[British Rail Class 755|Class 755]]\n| One train every two hours\n|-\n| [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]\n| {{rws|Norwich}} - {{rws|Brundall}} - {{rws|Cantley}} - Reedham - {{rws|Berney Arms}} (request stop) - {{rws|Great Yarmouth}}\n| [[British Rail Class 755|Class 755]]\n| Two trains a day in both directions\n|}\n\nOn Saturdays between February and May there is an additional train in both directions between Norwich and Great Yarmouth via Reedham, calling at Brundall and Reedham only. The ''down'' service (towards Yarmouth) departs Norwich at 05:32 and the ''up'' service (towards Norwich) departs Great Yarmouth at 23:34. <ref>https://www.greateranglia.co.uk/sites/default/files/assets/download_ct/20191115/g3QuBXav3gNQvCuLrppp2rT2evmhcVRQ97fVGWRUlWk/ga1912_table_8_web.pdf</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Reedham (Norfolk) railway station}}\n{{stn art lnk|REE|NR133EZ}}\n\n{{rail start}}\n{{rail line one to two|previous=[[Cantley railway station|Cantley]]|next1=[[Berney Arms railway station|Berney Arms]]|next2=[[Haddiscoe railway station|Haddiscoe]]|route1=[[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]<br><small>[[Wherry Lines]]<br>Great Yarmouth branch</small>|route2=[[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]<br><small>[[Wherry Lines]]<br>Lowestoft branch</small>|col={{NXEA colour}}}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{coord|52.565|N|1.560|E|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Norfolk]]\n[[Category:Former Great Eastern Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Greater Anglia franchise railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1844]]\n", "name_user": "Gregwholikestrains", "label": "safe", "comment": "