{"title_page": "Fordingbridge Hospital", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Fordingbridge Hospital\n| Org/Group   =[[Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust]] <!-- Org or group that owns/manages the hospital -->\n| Image       = Fordingbridge Hospital - geograph.org.uk - 61295.jpg<!-- Preferably photo of the main building or entrance-->\n| image alt   = \n| image_size  = \n| Caption     = Entrance showing Victorian part of hospital<!-- optional -->\n| map_type    =Hampshire\n| map_caption =Location in Hampshire\n| Logo        = <!-- Please conform to copyright -->\n| Logo Size   = <!-- Use to limit the logo size -->\n| Location    = \n| Region      = <!-- e.g. County or City - NB autolinked -->\n| State       = <!-- optional UK: England, Wales, Scotland, Northern Ireland. US: The US State - NB autolinked -->\n| Country     = <!-- 2 letter code or in full, United States must be \"US\" -->\n| Coordinates = {{coord|50.92752|-1.79292|display=inline,title}}\n| Address     = Bartons Road Fordingbridge, Hampshire<!-- Address of main building -->\n| HealthCare  = NHS<!-- UK:NHS. AU/CA: Medicare. ELSE freetext, e.g. Private -->\n| Funding     = Government<!-- Non-profit, For-profit, Government, Public - will generate linka -->\n| Type        = Community with out-patients department<!-- Community, District, General, District General, Teaching, Specialist -->\n| Speciality  = <!-- if devoted to a speciality (i.e. not a broad spectrum of specialities) and Type=Specialist/Teaching -->\n| Standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency   = No<!-- UK/IR/HK/SG: Yes/No, CA/IL/US: I/II/III/IV/V for Trauma certification level -->\n| Helipad     = <!-- Yes, No, or use \"Template:Airport codes\" with p=n. Only list if verifiable, leave blank if unknown. -->\n| Affiliation = <!-- 'None' or Medical School and university affiliations (medical or paramedical) -->\n| Patron      = <!-- 'None' or the individual who acts as the hospital patron -->\n| Network     = <!-- Hospital network, non-owner -->\n| Beds        = 21<!-- Cite in article as well -->\n| Founded     = <!-- Cite in article as well -->\n| Closed      = <!-- Use if defunct, please also add to Category:Defunct hospitals -->\n| Website     = <!-- 'None' or http URL -->\n| Wiki-Links  = <!-- Creates \"\"See also\" field -->\n}}\n'''Fordingbridge Hospital''' is a small [[community hospital]] in [[Fordingbridge]], [[Hampshire]], [[England]].  The hospital is on the same site as the previous Fordingbridge Infirmary and prior to that the Fordingbridge Workhouse.  The buildings are largely original Victorian with a modern ward for inpatients. It is managed by [[Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust]] based in Calmore, [[Southampton]].<ref name=southern>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Fordingbridge Hospital | work = | publisher = Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust | date = | url = http://www.southernhealth.nhs.uk/services/community-health-services/hospitals/fordingbridge/ | format = | doi =\n | accessdate = 22 April 2013 | archiveurl =  | archivedate = }}</ref>\n \n==History==\nThe hospital has its origins in the [[Workhouse|Union Workhouse]] built on a site at Bartons Road in 1885.{{efn|Replacing an earlier workhouse in Shaftesbury Road that had been destroyed by fire}} The site cost a little over \u00a39,000 and the buildings were erected in the [[Queen Anne style architecture|Queen Anne style]].<ref name=higginbotham>{{cite web | last = Higginbotham | first = Peter | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = The Workhouse, the Story of an Institution | work = Fordingbridge | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.workhouses.org.uk/Fordingbridge/ | format = | doi = | accessdate = 22 April 2013 | archiveurl =  | archivedate = }}</ref> In the 1930s the facility became a Public Assistance Institution and in 1948 it joined the  [[National Health Service]] as Fordingbridge Infirmary for the Chronic Sick.<ref name=higginbotham/>\n\nAfter the Fordingbridge Cottage Hospital at Highfield House on the Alderholt Road closed and its services were transferred to the Bartons Road site in 1984,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/written-answers/1986/dec/08/hospital-closures|title=Hospital closures|date=8 December 1986|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref> a modern facility, known as Ford Ward, opened on the Bartons Road site, which itself became known as Fordingbridge Hospital.<ref name=southern/>\n\n==Services==\nThe hospital provides 20 beds for older people and has physiotherapy and occupational therapy support. A small outpatient department in the older building accommodates a moderate range of specialities including: podiatry, ear, nose and throat services, audiology, speech and language therapy, continence service, dermatology services, stroke clinic services and dietitian services.<ref name=southern/><ref>{{cite web| title = Fordingbridge Hospital| publisher = NHS Choices| url = https://www.nhs.uk/Services/hospitals/Overview/DefaultView.aspx?id=94354| accessdate = 22 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of hospitals in England]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in the 1900s]]\n[[Category:Poor law infirmaries]]\n[[Category:Fordingbridge]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Fordingbridge Hospital\n| Org/Group   =[[Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust]] <!-- Org or group that owns/manages the hospital -->\n| Image       = Fordingbridge Hospital - geograph.org.uk - 61295.jpg<!-- Preferably photo of the main building or entrance-->\n| image alt   = \n| image_size  = \n| Caption     = Entrance showing Victorian part of hospital<!-- optional -->\n| map_type    =Hampshire\n| map_caption =Location in Hampshire\n| Logo        = <!-- Please conform to copyright -->\n| Logo Size   = <!-- Use to limit the logo size -->\n| Location    = \n| Region      = <!-- e.g. County or City - NB autolinked -->\n| State       = <!-- optional UK: England, Wales, Scotland, Northern Ireland. US: The US State - NB autolinked -->\n| Country     = <!-- 2 letter code or in full, United States must be \"US\" -->\n| Coordinates = {{coord|50.92752|-1.79292|display=inline,title}}\n| Address     = Bartons Road Fordingbridge, Hampshire<!-- Address of main building -->\n| HealthCare  = NHS<!-- UK:NHS. AU/CA: Medicare. ELSE freetext, e.g. Private -->\n| Funding     = Government<!-- Non-profit, For-profit, Government, Public - will generate linka -->\n| Type        = Community with out-patients department<!-- Community, District, General, District General, Teaching, Specialist -->\n| Speciality  = <!-- if devoted to a speciality (i.e. not a broad spectrum of specialities) and Type=Specialist/Teaching -->\n| Standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency   = No<!-- UK/IR/HK/SG: Yes/No, CA/IL/US: I/II/III/IV/V for Trauma certification level -->\n| Helipad     = <!-- Yes, No, or use \"Template:Airport codes\" with p=n. Only list if verifiable, leave blank if unknown. -->\n| Affiliation = <!-- 'None' or Medical School and university affiliations (medical or paramedical) -->\n| Patron      = <!-- 'None' or the individual who acts as the hospital patron -->\n| Network     = <!-- Hospital network, non-owner -->\n| Beds        = 21<!-- Cite in article as well -->\n| Founded     = <!-- Cite in article as well -->\n| Closed      = <!-- Use if defunct, please also add to Category:Defunct hospitals -->\n| Website     = <!-- 'None' or http URL -->\n| Wiki-Links  = <!-- Creates \"\"See also\" field -->\n}}\n'''Fordingbridge Hospital''' is a small [[community hospital]] in [[Fordingbridge]], [[Hampshire]], [[England]].  The hospital is on the same site as the previous Fordingbridge Infirmary and prior to that the Fordingbridge Workhouse.  The buildings are largely original Victorian with a modern ward for inpatients. It is managed by [[Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust]] based in Calmore, [[Southampton]].<ref name=southern>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Fordingbridge Hospital | work = | publisher = Southern Health NHS Foundation Trust | date = | url = http://www.southernhealth.nhs.uk/services/community-health-services/hospitals/fordingbridge/ | format = | doi =\n | accessdate = 22 April 2013 | archiveurl =  | archivedate = }}</ref>\n \n==History==\nThe hospital has its origins in the [[Workhouse|Union Workhouse]] built on a site at Bartons Road in 1885.{{efn|Replacing an earlier workhouse in Shaftesbury Road that had been destroyed by fire}} The site cost a little over \u00a39,000 and the buildings were erected in the [[Queen Anne style architecture|Queen Anne style]].<ref name=higginbotham>{{cite web | last = Higginbotham | first = Peter | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = The Workhouse, the Story of an Institution | work = Fordingbridge | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.workhouses.org.uk/Fordingbridge/ | format = | doi = | accessdate = 22 April 2013 | archiveurl =  | archivedate = }}</ref> In the 1930s the facility became a Public Assistance Institution and in 1948 it joined the  [[National Health Service]] as Fordingbridge Infirmary for the Chronic Sick.<ref name=higginbotham/>\n\nAfter the Fordingbridge Cottage Hospital at Highfield House on the Alderholt Road closed and its services were transferred to the Bartons Road site in 1984,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/written-answers/1986/dec/08/hospital-closures|title=Hospital closures|date=8 December 1986|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref> a modern facility, known as Ford Ward, opened on the Bartons Road site, which itself became known as Fordingbridge Hospital.<ref name=southern/>\n\n==Services==\nThe hospital provides 20 beds for older people and has physiotherapy and occupational therapy support. A small outpatient department in the older building accommodates a moderate range of specialities including: podiatry, ear, nose and throat services, audiology, speech and language therapy, continence service, dermatology services, stroke clinic services and dietitian services.<ref name=southern/><ref>{{cite web| title = Fordingbridge Hospital| publisher = NHS Choices| url = https://www.nhs.uk/Services/hospitals/Overview/DefaultView.aspx?id=94354| accessdate = 22 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of hospitals in England]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in the 1900s]]\n[[Category:Poor law infirmaries]]\n[[Category:Fordingbridge]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fordingbridge_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Fleming Memorial Hospital", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       =Fleming Memorial Hospital\n| image=Former Fleming Memorial Hospital, Abbotsford Terrace (geograph 3599866).jpg\n| caption=Fleming Memorial Hospital in Jesmond\n| Org/Group  =\n| Logo       = <!-- optional -->\n| Location   = Newcastle upon Tyne\n| map_type   = United Kingdom Newcastle-upon-Tyne#Tyne and Wear\n| map_caption = Location in Newcastle upon Tyne##Location in Tyne and Wear\n| coordinates = {{coord|54.9868|-1.6135|display=inline,title}}\n| Country    = England\n| HealthCare = [[NHS England]]\n| Type       = Children's services\n| Speciality = <!-- if devoted to a speciality, i.e. not if has broad spectrum of specialities -->\n| Standards  = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Affiliation= \n| Beds       = \n| Founded    = 1863\n| Closed     = 1988\n| Website    = \n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n}}\n'''Fleming Memorial Hospital''' was a children's health facility in Abbotsford Terrace, [[Jesmond]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne]]. It is a Grade II [[listed building]].<ref>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1242077|desc=Fleming Memorial Hospital}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe hospital has its origins in the Children's Hospital established by Dr Joseph Fife and Dr William Murray in Hanover Square in Newcastle upon Tyne in 1863.<ref name=na>{{cite web|url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/456069d8-f81a-4e69-a55f-1783a0a6c126|title=Fleming Memorial Hospital for sick children|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Redhead|first=Lynn|title=Hospitals: Newcastle Revisited|publisher=Newcastle Libraries and Information Service|year=1996|isbn=9781857950977}}</ref> After the Children's Hospital established in Hanover Square was deemed inadequate, a new facility, which was designed by John Quilter and George Wheelhouse and financed with a donation by John Fleming, a local solicitor, was officially opened in [[Jesmond]] by [[William Armstrong, 1st Baron Armstrong|Lord Armstrong]] in September 1888.<ref name=na/> After children's services transferred to the [[Royal Victoria Infirmary]], the Fleming Memorial Hospital closed in 1988 and the building was converted for commercial use as the Fleming Business Centre in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adderstonegroup.com/developments/project-portfolio/the-fleming/|title=The Fleming|publisher=The Adderstone Group|accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1888]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:1863 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Defunct hospitals in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       =Fleming Memorial Hospital\n| image=Former Fleming Memorial Hospital, Abbotsford Terrace (geograph 3599866).jpg\n| caption=Fleming Memorial Hospital in Jesmond\n| Org/Group  =\n| Logo       = <!-- optional -->\n| Location   = Newcastle upon Tyne\n| map_type   = United Kingdom Newcastle-upon-Tyne#Tyne and Wear\n| map_caption = Location in Newcastle upon Tyne##Location in Tyne and Wear\n| coordinates = {{coord|54.9868|-1.6135|display=inline,title}}\n| Country    = England\n| HealthCare = [[NHS England]]\n| Type       = Children's services\n| Speciality = <!-- if devoted to a speciality, i.e. not if has broad spectrum of specialities -->\n| Standards  = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Affiliation= \n| Beds       = \n| Founded    = 1863\n| Closed     = 1988\n| Website    = \n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n}}\n'''Fleming Memorial Hospital''' was a children's health facility in Abbotsford Terrace, [[Jesmond]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne]]. It is a Grade II [[listed building]].<ref>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1242077|desc=Fleming Memorial Hospital}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe hospital has its origins in the Children's Hospital established by Dr Joseph Fife and Dr William Murray in Hanover Square in Newcastle upon Tyne in 1863.<ref name=na>{{cite web|url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/456069d8-f81a-4e69-a55f-1783a0a6c126|title=Fleming Memorial Hospital for sick children|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Redhead|first=Lynn|title=Hospitals: Newcastle Revisited|publisher=Newcastle Libraries and Information Service|year=1996|isbn=9781857950977}}</ref> After the Children's Hospital established in Hanover Square was deemed inadequate, a new facility, which was designed by John Quilter and George Wheelhouse and financed with a donation by John Fleming, a local solicitor, was officially opened in [[Jesmond]] by [[William Armstrong, 1st Baron Armstrong|Lord Armstrong]] in September 1888.<ref name=na/> After children's services transferred to the [[Royal Victoria Infirmary]], the Fleming Memorial Hospital closed in 1988 and the building was converted for commercial use as the Fleming Business Centre in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adderstonegroup.com/developments/project-portfolio/the-fleming/|title=The Fleming|publisher=The Adderstone Group|accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1888]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Tyne and Wear]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:1863 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Defunct hospitals in England]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fleming_Memorial_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Fleming Cottage Hospital", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Fleming Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[NHS Grampian]] \n| Image      = The Fleming Hospital at Aberlour - geograph.org.uk - 1620222.jpg\n| Caption    = Fleming Cottage Hospital\n| Logo       = <!-- optional -->\n| Location   = [[Aberlour]]\n| Region     = Banffshire \n| State      = Scotland \n| Country    = UK\n| HealthCare = NHS\n| Type       = General\n| Speciality = \n| Emergency  = Minor injuries unit\n| Affiliation= <!-- University or Medical School -->\n| Beds       = 15\n| Founded    = 1990\n| Closed     = <!-- optional -->\n| Website    = \n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   =Scotland Moray\n| map_caption=Shown in Moray\n| coordinates={{coord|57|28|9|N|3|13|22|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|}}\n'''Fleming Hospital''' is a [[UK]] [[National Health Service]] [[hospital]] in [[Aberlour]], [[Morayshire]], [[Scotland]]. It is administered by [[NHS Grampian]].\n\n==History==\nThe hospital, which was financed by a legacy from James Fleming (1830-1895), the distiller, and designed by [[James Leslie Findlay]], was opened in April 1900.<ref>{{cite web | title=Fleming Cottage Hospital | work=Dictionary of Scottish Architects | url=http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/building_full.php?id=227286 |accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nFleming Hospital was purpose built and is physically adjoined to the local health centre providing GP, community nursing and other primary care services. It has 15 beds providing medical care, rehabilitation, assessment, palliative/terminal care, convalescence and respite care. The hospital also has a minor injuries unit, which is open 24 hours a day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.know-who-to-turn-to.com/minor_injuries_clinic2.html |title=Know who to turn to: Local minor injury units |publisher=NHS Grampian |accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref> General medical and surgical out patient clinics are held on site.<ref>{{cite web | title=Fleming Hospital |work=NHS Grampian |url=http://www.nhsgrampian.org/nhsgrampian/gra_display_simple_index.jsp?pContentID=2450&p_applic=CCC&p_service=Content.show& | date=2 May 2014 |accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Social work}}\n{{Hospitals in NHS Grampian}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1900]]\n[[Category:NHS Grampian]]\n[[Category:NHS Scotland hospitals]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Moray]]\n[[Category:Cottage hospitals]]\n[[Category:1900 establishments in Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox Hospital\n| Name       = Fleming Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[NHS Grampian]] \n| Image      = The Fleming Hospital at Aberlour - geograph.org.uk - 1620222.jpg\n| Caption    = Fleming Cottage Hospital\n| Logo       = <!-- optional -->\n| Location   = [[Aberlour]]\n| Region     = Banffshire \n| State      = Scotland \n| Country    = UK\n| HealthCare = NHS\n| Type       = General\n| Speciality = \n| Emergency  = Minor injuries unit\n| Affiliation= <!-- University or Medical School -->\n| Beds       = 15\n| Founded    = 1990\n| Closed     = <!-- optional -->\n| Website    = \n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   =Scotland Moray\n| map_caption=Shown in Moray\n| coordinates={{coord|57|28|9|N|3|13|22|W|region:GB_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|}}\n'''Fleming Hospital''' is a [[UK]] [[National Health Service]] [[hospital]] in [[Aberlour]], [[Morayshire]], [[Scotland]]. It is administered by [[NHS Grampian]].\n\n==History==\nThe hospital, which was financed by a legacy from James Fleming (1830-1895), the distiller, and designed by [[James Leslie Findlay]], was opened in April 1900.<ref>{{cite web | title=Fleming Cottage Hospital | work=Dictionary of Scottish Architects | url=http://www.scottisharchitects.org.uk/building_full.php?id=227286 |accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nFleming Hospital was purpose built and is physically adjoined to the local health centre providing GP, community nursing and other primary care services. It has 15 beds providing medical care, rehabilitation, assessment, palliative/terminal care, convalescence and respite care. The hospital also has a minor injuries unit, which is open 24 hours a day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.know-who-to-turn-to.com/minor_injuries_clinic2.html |title=Know who to turn to: Local minor injury units |publisher=NHS Grampian |accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref> General medical and surgical out patient clinics are held on site.<ref>{{cite web | title=Fleming Hospital |work=NHS Grampian |url=http://www.nhsgrampian.org/nhsgrampian/gra_display_simple_index.jsp?pContentID=2450&p_applic=CCC&p_service=Content.show& | date=2 May 2014 |accessdate=8 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Social work}}\n{{Hospitals in NHS Grampian}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1900]]\n[[Category:NHS Grampian]]\n[[Category:NHS Scotland hospitals]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Moray]]\n[[Category:Cottage hospitals]]\n[[Category:1900 establishments in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fleming_Cottage_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Finchley Memorial Hospital", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Finchley Memorial Hospital\n| Org/Group   = Barnet Clinical Commissioning Group\n| Image       = Finchley Memorial Hospital.JPG\n| Caption     = Finchley Memorial Hospital\n| Logo        = <!-- optional -->\n| Logo Size   = <!-- optional -->\n| Location   = [[North Finchley]]\n| Region     = London\n| State      = England\n| Country    = UK\n| HealthCare = [[NHS England]]\n| Type       = Community\n| Speciality = <!-- Only if especially notable -->\n| Emergency  = No\n| Affiliation= \n| Beds       =  \n| Founded    = 1908\n| Closed     = <!-- optional -->\n| Website    = {{url|http://www.barnetccg.nhs.uk/urgent-care-and-walk-in-centres.htm}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| Coordinates={{coord|51.6056|-0.1763|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type    = United Kingdom London Barnet\n| map_caption = Location within Barnet\n}}\nThe '''Finchley Memorial Hospital''' is a [[NHS Barnet|National Health Service]] [[community hospital]] in Granville Road, [[North Finchley]], [[London]]. It is managed by Barnet Clinical Commissioning Group.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Finchley Memorial Hospital - geograph.org.uk - 119298.jpg|thumb|left|The former hospital buildings]]\nThe hospital was originally established as the Finchley Cottage Hospital and opened with 20 beds in May 1908.<ref name=lost>{{cite web|url=https://ezitis.myzen.co.uk/finchleymemorial.html |title=Finchley Memorial Hospital |website=Lost hospitals of London |date=June 2010 |accessdate=9 May 2018}}</ref> An extension financed by public subscription which would form a lasting memorial for the Finchley dead of the [[World War I|First World War]] was opened by General [[Ian Hamilton (British Army officer)|Sir Ian Hamilton]] in 1922.<ref name=lost/> The facility was renamed the Finchley Memorial Hospital that year.<ref name=lost/>\n\nA casualty department opened in 1926 and a two-story accommodation block for nurses opened in 1933.<ref name=lost/> A geriatric day facility was opened by [[Margaret Thatcher]], the local [[Member of parliament|MP]], in January 1987.<ref name=lost/>\n\nA new three-storey hospital building was procured under a [[Private Finance Initiative]] contract in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.london.gov.uk/what-we-do/planning/planning-applications-and-decisions/planning-application-search/finchley|title=Finchley|publisher=Mayor of London|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref> It was built by [[Galliford Try]] at a cost of \u00a328 million and was opened by the [[Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester|Duke of Gloucester]] in September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buildingconstructiondesign.co.uk/news/duke-of-gloucester-officially-opens-finchley-memorial-hospital/|title=Duke of Gloucester officially opens Finchley Memorial Hospital|date=27 September 2013|publisher=Building Construction Design|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\nThe hospital does not include an [[accident and emergency department]], but it does offer a walk-in centre for minor injuries that do not present an immediate threat to life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhs.uk/Services/clinics/Overview/DefaultView.aspx?id=92277|title=Finchley NHS Walk-In Centre|publisher=NHS Choices|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Finchley Memorial Hospital}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Finchley]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in London]]\n\n\n{{Hospital-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Finchley Memorial Hospital\n| Org/Group   = Barnet Clinical Commissioning Group\n| Image       = Finchley Memorial Hospital.JPG\n| Caption     = Finchley Memorial Hospital\n| Logo        = <!-- optional -->\n| Logo Size   = <!-- optional -->\n| Location   = [[North Finchley]]\n| Region     = London\n| State      = England\n| Country    = UK\n| HealthCare = [[NHS England]]\n| Type       = Community\n| Speciality = <!-- Only if especially notable -->\n| Emergency  = No\n| Affiliation= \n| Beds       =  \n| Founded    = 1908\n| Closed     = <!-- optional -->\n| Website    = {{url|http://www.barnetccg.nhs.uk/urgent-care-and-walk-in-centres.htm}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n| Coordinates={{coord|51.6056|-0.1763|display=inline,title}}\n| map_type    = United Kingdom London Barnet\n| map_caption = Location within Barnet\n}}\nThe '''Finchley Memorial Hospital''' is a [[NHS Barnet|National Health Service]] [[community hospital]] in Granville Road, [[North Finchley]], [[London]]. It is managed by Barnet Clinical Commissioning Group.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Finchley Memorial Hospital - geograph.org.uk - 119298.jpg|thumb|left|The former hospital buildings]]\nThe hospital was originally established as the Finchley Cottage Hospital and opened with 20 beds in May 1908.<ref name=lost>{{cite web|url=https://ezitis.myzen.co.uk/finchleymemorial.html |title=Finchley Memorial Hospital |website=Lost hospitals of London |date=June 2010 |accessdate=9 May 2018}}</ref> An extension financed by public subscription which would form a lasting memorial for the Finchley dead of the [[World War I|First World War]] was opened by General [[Ian Hamilton (British Army officer)|Sir Ian Hamilton]] in 1922.<ref name=lost/> The facility was renamed the Finchley Memorial Hospital that year.<ref name=lost/>\n\nA casualty department opened in 1926 and a two-story accommodation block for nurses opened in 1933.<ref name=lost/> A geriatric day facility was opened by [[Margaret Thatcher]], the local [[Member of parliament|MP]], in January 1987.<ref name=lost/>\n\nA new three-storey hospital building was procured under a [[Private Finance Initiative]] contract in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.london.gov.uk/what-we-do/planning/planning-applications-and-decisions/planning-application-search/finchley|title=Finchley|publisher=Mayor of London|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref> It was built by [[Galliford Try]] at a cost of \u00a328 million and was opened by the [[Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester|Duke of Gloucester]] in September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buildingconstructiondesign.co.uk/news/duke-of-gloucester-officially-opens-finchley-memorial-hospital/|title=Duke of Gloucester officially opens Finchley Memorial Hospital|date=27 September 2013|publisher=Building Construction Design|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Facilities==\nThe hospital does not include an [[accident and emergency department]], but it does offer a walk-in centre for minor injuries that do not present an immediate threat to life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nhs.uk/Services/clinics/Overview/DefaultView.aspx?id=92277|title=Finchley NHS Walk-In Centre|publisher=NHS Choices|accessdate=27 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Finchley Memorial Hospital}}\n\n[[Category:Finchley]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in London]]\n\n\n{{Hospital-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finchley_Memorial_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Old Town, Florida", "text_new": "{{short description|Human settlement in Florida, United States}}\n[[File:Old Town Methodist Church04.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Old Town Methodist Church]]]]\n[[File:Old Town Elem School02.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Old Town Elementary School (Old Town, Florida)|Old Town Elementary School]]]]\n'''Old Town''' is an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in [[Dixie County, Florida|Dixie County]], [[Florida]], United States, located at [[U.S. Route 19 in Florida|US 19]]\u2013[[U.S. Route 27 Alternate (Florida)|ALT 27]]-[[U.S. Route 98 in Florida|98]] and [[State Road 349 (Florida)|State Road 349]].\n\n==Geography==\nOld Town is located at {{coord|29.6011|-82.9819|type:city_region:US|format=dms|display=inline,title}} (29.6011, -82.9819),<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> about 40 miles southwest of [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]] and 12 miles northwest of [[Chiefland, Florida|Chiefland]].\n\n==Historic places==\nHistoric places in Old Town include:\n* ''[[City of Hawkinsville (shipwreck)|City of Hawkinsville]]'', a shipwreck in the [[Suwannee River]], near the Nature Coast Trail State Park\n* [[Old Town Methodist Church]] built in 1890, located behind the 1983 church building.\n* [[Old Town Elementary School (Old Town, Florida)|Old Town Elementary School]], now the Dixie County Cultural Center\n\n==Medical care==\nFor health care, Old Town has a small urgent-care center; but in emergencies, patients are airlifted to [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]] hospitals. Physical therapy and other rehabilitative services are available in [[Chiefland, Florida|Chiefland]].\n\n==Education==\nResidents are served by [[Dixie District Schools]]. Old Town Elementary School is located in Old Town.<ref>[http://aplusweb.dixie.k12.fl.us/~otes@dixie.k12.fl.us/?OpenItemURL=S007357E1 Home]. Old Town Elementary School. Retrieved on February 2, 2017.</ref> Old Town is also served by secondary schools in [[Cross City, Florida|Cross City]]: Ruth Rains Middle School,<ref>[http://aplusweb.dixie.k12.fl.us/~rrms@dixie.k12.fl.us/ Home]. Ruth Rains Middle School. Retrieved on February 2, 2017.</ref> and [[Dixie County High School]].<ref>[http://aplusweb.dixie.k12.fl.us/~dchs@dixie.k12.fl.us/ Home]. [[Dixie County High School]]. Retrieved on February 2, 2017.</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n[[Guy Gabaldon]], World War II Marine who had convinced some 1,300 Japanese soldiers to surrender on [[Saipan]] and [[Tinian]] islands.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Dixie County, Florida}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Dixie County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Florida]]\n\n\n{{DixieCountyFL-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Human settlement in Florida, United States of America}}\n[[File:Old Town Methodist Church04.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Old Town Methodist Church]]]]\n[[File:Old Town Elem School02.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Old Town Elementary School (Old Town, Florida)|Old Town Elementary School]]]]\n'''Old Town''' is an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in [[Dixie County, Florida|Dixie County]], [[Florida]], United States, located at [[U.S. Route 19 in Florida|US 19]]-[[U.S. Route 27 Alternate (Florida)|ALT 27]]-[[U.S. Route 98 in Florida|98]] and [[State Road 349 (Florida)|State Road 349]].\n\n==Geography==\nOld Town is located at {{coord|29.6011|-82.9819|type:city_region:US|format=dms|display=inline,title}} (29.6011, -82.9819),<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> about 40 miles southwest of [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]] and 12 miles northwest of [[Chiefland, Florida|Chiefland]].\n\n==Historic places==\nHistoric places in Old Town include:\n* ''[[City of Hawkinsville (shipwreck)|City of Hawkinsville]]'', a shipwreck in the [[Suwannee River]], near the Nature Coast Trail State Park\n* [[Old Town Methodist Church]] built in 1890, located behind the 1983 church building.\n* [[Old Town Elementary School (Old Town, Florida)|Old Town Elementary School]], now the Dixie County Cultural Center\n\n==Medical care==\nFor health care, Old Town has a small urgent-care center; but in emergencies, patients are airlifted to [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]] hospitals. Physical therapy and other rehabilitative services are available in [[Chiefland, Florida|Chiefland]].\n\n==Education==\nResidents are served by [[Dixie District Schools]]. Old Town Elementary School is located in Old Town.<ref>[http://aplusweb.dixie.k12.fl.us/~otes@dixie.k12.fl.us/?OpenItemURL=S007357E1 Home]. Old Town Elementary School. Retrieved on February 2, 2017.</ref> Old Town is also served by secondary schools in [[Cross City, Florida|Cross City]]: Ruth Rains Middle School,<ref>[http://aplusweb.dixie.k12.fl.us/~rrms@dixie.k12.fl.us/ Home]. Ruth Rains Middle School. Retrieved on February 2, 2017.</ref> and [[Dixie County High School]].<ref>[http://aplusweb.dixie.k12.fl.us/~dchs@dixie.k12.fl.us/ Home]. [[Dixie County High School]]. Retrieved on February 2, 2017.</ref>\n\n==Notable residents==\n[[Guy Gabaldon]], World War II Marine who had convinced some 1,300 Japanese soldiers to surrender on [[Saipan]] and [[Tinian]] islands.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Dixie County, Florida}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Dixie County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Unincorporated communities in Florida]]\n\n\n{{DixieCountyFL-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Srich32977", "label": "safe", "comment": "shorten short", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Town,_Florida"}
{"title_page": "Cotter, Arkansas", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Cotter, Arkansas\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|motto                    = \"Trout capital U.S.A.\"\n|image_skyline            = Cotter Bridge, Baxter County, Arkansas.JPG\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = Cotter Bridge over the White River\n|image_seal               = \n|image_map                = File:Baxter County Arkansas Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Cotter Highlighted 0515490.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Cotter in Baxter County, Arkansas.\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Arkansas|County]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Arkansas]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Baxter County, Arkansas|Baxter]]\n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|established_date         = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 6.26\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 2.42\n|area_land_km2            = 6.22\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 2.40\n|area_water_km2           = 0.04\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.02\n|elevation_ft             = 633\n|elevation_m              = 193\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 970\n|population_metro         = \n|population_density_km2   = 150.91\n|population_density_sq_mi = 390.83\n|timezone                 = [[Central Time Zone (North America)|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|coordinates              = {{coord|36|16|29|N|92|31|42|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 72626\n|area_code                = [[Area code 870|870]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 05-15490\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0076681\n|footnotes                = \n|website                  = {{URL|http://www.cotterweb.com}}\n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 942\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_05.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Aug 22, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Cotter''' is a city in [[Baxter County, Arkansas|Baxter County]], [[Arkansas]], United States. The population was 970 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Cotter Bridge Spanning White River wide.jpg|left|250px|thumb|The [[Cotter Bridge]] was critical in the development of The Ozarks.]]\n[[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] Bluff Dwellers were the original inhabitants of the area now known as Cotter. When Native Americans were moved westward on the [[Trail of Tears]], approximately 1000 [[Cherokees]] crossed just a short distance upriver from the current location of Downtown Cotter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cotterar.com/history/aramey1.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-08-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110115114330/http://www.cotterar.com/history/aramey1.htm |archive-date=2011-01-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Exploration and settlement===\nIn 1819, [[Henry Schoolcraft]] was exploring the Ozarks and spent a night in the Cotter area. He said of the area,<ref>Scenes and Adventures in the Semi-Alpine Regions of the Ozark of Missouri and Arkansas (1853) pg 120-121</ref>\n <blockquote>White River is one of the most beautiful and enchanting streams, and by far the most transparent, which discharge their waters into the Mississippi ... We here behold the assembled tributaries                flowing in a smooth, broad. deep, and majestic current ...                skirted at a short distance by mountains of the most imposing                grandeur.... [The] extreme limpidity and want of colour ... was                early seized upon by the French traders on first visiting this                stream, in calling it \"La Rivi\u00e8re Blanche\" (White                River).</blockquote>\n\nFuture President, [[Herbert Hoover]], spent the summer of 1892 helping [[Geologist]] [[John C. Branner]] survey the Northern [[Ozarks]]. By the early 1900s, there were many mining companies active in both Baxter, and [[Marion County, Arkansas|Marion]] Counties. Cotter quickly became a central point where minerals could be shipped via [[Steamboat]] to much larger cities in Central Arkansas or Southern [[Missouri]].\n\nOriginally, the river bend was known as either Lake's Ferry or Lake's Landing. At this spot, the [[White River (Arkansas)|White River]] turns sharply, making a convenient border for a town. The Spring that rises up from the caves beneath Cotter, also added to the appeal to early settlers. Lake's Ferry was known as one of the most beautiful spots on the river and was appreciated by locals and tourists.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.railroadworkersmemorial.com/cotterhistory.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-04-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821143359/http://www.railroadworkersmemorial.com/cotterhistory.htm |archive-date=2013-08-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===The railroad===\nSeeking to capitalize on the growing trade in the area, the [[Missouri-Pacific Railroad]] announced plans to open the White River Line which would run through the area and would connect with the main line in Lake's Landing. By 1902, the Cotter post office had opened. Two years later, the first school in Cotter opened. In 1905, the Missouri Pacific Railroad bought the area and sold over one thousand lots, mostly to railroad employees.<ref>Bennett, Lola and Smith, Corinne. \"Historic American Engineering Record Cotter Bridge (R.M. Ruthven Bridge).\" 1988.[http://www.arkansashighways.com/historic_bridge/HAER%20Documents/AR-15%20Cotter%20Bridge%20(00702).pdf History.] Page 3. Retrieved August 20, 2010.</ref> The city was incorporated in 1905 as Cotter, Arkansas.<ref>Ramey, Ann. \"Cotter Historical Briefs.\" [http://www.cotterar.com/history/aramey1.htm History.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110115114330/http://www.cotterar.com/history/aramey1.htm |date=2011-01-15 }} Retrieved August 20, 2010.</ref> By that time, the population was over 600. The town was named after William Cotter, an official for the Missouri Pacific Railway System, which built a line through the small town. The materials required to build the town and railroad had to be brought in by steamboats down the White River. Once the railroad was completed, the use of steamboats on the rivers of Arkansas decreased and eventually ceased altogether. In 1906, the first passenger train arrived, and the tourist era began.\n\n===The Bridge===\n\nThe mercurial [[White River (Arkansas)|White River]] caused many motorists problems, as the nearest crossing was over {{convert|100|mi|km}} to the north in [[Branson, Missouri]]. An inconvenient ferry system made the need for a bridge apparent. Locals wanted a bridge, but they strongly opposed a toll bridge.<ref>Bennett, Lola and Smith, Corinne. \"Historic American Engineering Record Cotter Bridge (R.M. Ruthven Bridge).\" 1988. [http://www.arkansashighways.com/historic_bridge/HAER%20Documents/AR-15%20Cotter%20Bridge%20(00702).pdf History.] Page 6. Retrieved August 20, 2010.</ref> Arkansas did not have a central highway body at the time, and was instead a patchwork of [[Transportation of Arkansas#The \"district approach\" dooms hopes of unity|\"road districts\"]], which made the bridge-building efforts even more difficult. Without a toll, funding wasn't available until [[Arkansas Highway 12]] was redesignated [[U.S. Route 62]] in 1930. The [[Cotter Bridge]] was constructed through the area using a unique rainbow arch design.\n\n==Geography==\nCotter is located at {{coord|36|16|29|N|92|31|42|W|type:city}} (36.274772, -92.528336).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|2.5|sqmi|km2}}, all land.\n\n=== Transportation ===\n\n==== List of highways ====\n*[[Image:US 62 (1961).svg|20px]][[Image:US 412.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Route 62 in Arkansas|US 62]]/[[U.S. Route 412 in Arkansas|US 412]]\n*[[File:US 62B.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Route 62 Business (Mountain Home, Arkansas)|U.S. Route 62 Business]]\n*[[Image:Arkansas 345.svg|24px]] [[Arkansas Highway 345]]\n\n==== Railroads ====\nCotter has one local railroad, the Missouri and Northern Arkansas Railroad. The MNA leases the track from [[Newport, Arkansas|Newport]] to [[Kansas City, Missouri]], from the [[Union Pacific Railroad|Union Pacific]]. The regular train traffic are empty coal trains from The Independence power plant, as well as a north and south local out of Cotter.\n\n==== Airports ====\nCotter is accessible to two separate commercial airports, Ozark Regional Airport (Baxter County) and Flippin Municipal Airport \n(Marion County). There is also a rural air field, Valley Airport, located on Denton Ferry Road that serves small planes owned by residents.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1910= 894\n|1920= 884\n|1930= 1064\n|1940= 903\n|1950= 1089\n|1960= 683\n|1970= 858\n|1980= 920\n|1990= 867\n|2000= 921\n|2010= 970\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=942\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref> of 2010, there were 1,078 people, 472 households and 293 families residing in the city.  The [[population density]] was 373.6 people per square mile (144.0/km\u00b2).  There were 501 housing units at an average density of 203.2 per square mile (78.3/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the city was 97.07% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 0.87% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.22% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], and 1.85% from two or more races.  1.52% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 545<ref name=\"American Fact Finder\">{{cite web | url=https://www.census.gov | title=2010 Census Results | accessdate=April 9, 2011}}</ref> households out of which 20.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 48.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 8.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 40.0% were non-families. 35.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 16.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.08 and the average family size was 2.67.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 19.7% under the age of 18, 8.7% from 18 to 24, 24.8% from 25 to 44, 26.7% from 45 to 64, and 20.2% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 43 years. For every 100 females, there were 97.2 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 99.5 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $22,857, and the median income for a family was $34,375. Males had a median income of $26,298 versus $17,266 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $15,893.  About 11.9% of families and 16.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 18.3% of those under age 18 and 13.3% of those age 65 or over.\n\n== Education ==\nPublic education is provided by the Cotter School District including [[Cotter High School (Cotter, Arkansas)|Cotter High School]] (grades 7 through 12) and Amanda Gist Elementary School (kindergarten through grade 6).<ref>{{Cite map\n  |publisher = US Census Bureau\n  |title = School District Reference Map (2010 Census) Baxter County, AR\n  |url = http://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/dc10map/sch_dist/st05_ar/c05005_baxter/DC10SD_C05005_001.pdf\n  |accessdate = 2011-07-12 }}</ref>\n\n==Notable People==\n\n*[[Gene Wesley Harris]]- fire chief and politician.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www2.census.gov/geo/pvs/bas/bas11/st05_ar/incplace/p0515490_cotter/BAS11P10500015490_001.pdf Map of Cotter] (US Census Bureau)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121019104620/http://www2.census.gov/geo/pvs/bas/bas11/st05_ar/cou/c05005_baxter/BAS11C20500500000_000.pdf Map of Baxter County] (US Census Bureau)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100528153130/http://www.baxtercountyhistory.org/ Baxter County Historical and Genealogical Society]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Baxter County, Arkansas}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Baxter County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Cities in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1905]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Cotter, Arkansas\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|motto                    = \"Trout capital U.S.A.\"\n|image_skyline            = Cotter Bridge, Baxter County, Arkansas.JPG\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = Cotter Bridge over the White River\n|image_seal               = \n|image_map                = File:Baxter County Arkansas Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Cotter Highlighted 0515490.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Cotter in Baxter County, Arkansas.\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Arkansas|County]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Arkansas]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Baxter County, Arkansas|Baxter]]\n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|established_date         = \n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 6.26\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 2.42\n|area_land_km2            = 6.22\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 2.40\n|area_water_km2           = 0.04\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.02\n|elevation_ft             = 633\n|elevation_m              = 193\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 970\n|population_metro         = \n|population_density_km2   = 150.91\n|population_density_sq_mi = 390.83\n|timezone                 = [[Central Time Zone (North America)|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|coordinates              = {{coord|36|16|29|N|92|31|42|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 72626\n|area_code                = [[Area code 870|870]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 05-15490\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0076681\n|footnotes                = \n|website                  = {{URL|http://www.cotterweb.com}}\n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 942\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_05.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Aug 22, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Cotter''' is a city in [[Baxter County, Arkansas|Baxter County]], [[Arkansas]], United States. The population was 970 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Cotter Bridge Spanning White River wide.jpg|left|250px|thumb|The [[Cotter Bridge]] was critical in the development of The Ozarks.]]\n[[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] Bluff Dwellers were the original inhabitants of the area now known as Cotter. When Native Americans were moved westward on the [[Trail of Tears]], approximately 1000 [[Cherokees]] crossed just a short distance upriver from the current location of Downtown Cotter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cotterar.com/history/aramey1.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-08-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110115114330/http://www.cotterar.com/history/aramey1.htm |archive-date=2011-01-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Exploration and settlement===\nIn 1819, [[Henry Schoolcraft]] was exploring the Ozarks and spent a night in the Cotter area. He said of the area,<ref>Scenes and Adventures in the Semi-Alpine Regions of the Ozark of Missouri and Arkansas (1853) pg 120-121</ref>\n <blockquote>White River is one of the most beautiful and enchanting streams, and by far the most transparent, which discharge their waters into the Mississippi ... We here behold the assembled tributaries                flowing in a smooth, broad. deep, and majestic current ...                skirted at a short distance by mountains of the most imposing                grandeur.... [The] extreme limpidity and want of colour ... was                early seized upon by the French traders on first visiting this                stream, in calling it \"La Rivi\u00e8re Blanche\" (White                River).</blockquote>\n\nFuture President, [[Herbert Hoover]], spent the summer of 1892 helping [[Geologist]] [[John C. Branner]] survey the Northern [[Ozarks]]. By the early 1900s, there were many mining companies active in both Baxter, and [[Marion County, Arkansas|Marion]] Counties. Cotter quickly became a central point where minerals could be shipped via [[Steamboat]] to much larger cities in Central Arkansas or Southern [[Missouri]].\n\nOriginally, the river bend was known as either Lake's Ferry or Lake's Landing. At this spot, the [[White River (Arkansas)|White River]] turns sharply, making a convenient border for a town. The Spring that rises up from the caves beneath Cotter, also added to the appeal to early settlers. Lake's Ferry was known as one of the most beautiful spots on the river and was appreciated by locals and tourists.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.railroadworkersmemorial.com/cotterhistory.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-04-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821143359/http://www.railroadworkersmemorial.com/cotterhistory.htm |archive-date=2013-08-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===The railroad===\nSeeking to capitalize on the growing trade in the area, the [[Missouri-Pacific Railroad]] announced plans to open the White River Line which would run through the area and would connect with the main line in Lake's Landing. By 1902, the Cotter post office had opened. Two years later, the first school in Cotter opened. In 1905, the Missouri Pacific Railroad bought the area and sold over one thousand lots, mostly to railroad employees.<ref>Bennett, Lola and Smith, Corinne. \"Historic American Engineering Record Cotter Bridge (R.M. Ruthven Bridge).\" 1988.[http://www.arkansashighways.com/historic_bridge/HAER%20Documents/AR-15%20Cotter%20Bridge%20(00702).pdf History.] Page 3. Retrieved August 20, 2010.</ref> The city was incorporated in 1905 as Cotter, Arkansas.<ref>Ramey, Ann. \"Cotter Historical Briefs.\" [http://www.cotterar.com/history/aramey1.htm History.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110115114330/http://www.cotterar.com/history/aramey1.htm |date=2011-01-15 }} Retrieved August 20, 2010.</ref> By that time, the population was over 600. The town was named after William Cotter, an official for the Missouri Pacific Railway System, which built a line through the small town. The materials required to build the town and railroad had to be brought in by steamboats down the White River. Once the railroad was completed, the use of steamboats on the rivers of Arkansas decreased and eventually ceased altogether. In 1906, the first passenger train arrived, and the tourist era began.\n\n===The Bridge===\n\nThe mercurial [[White River (Arkansas)|White River]] caused many motorists problems, as the nearest crossing was over {{convert|100|mi|km}} to the north in [[Branson, Missouri]]. An inconvenient ferry system made the need for a bridge apparent. Locals wanted a bridge, but they strongly opposed a toll bridge.<ref>Bennett, Lola and Smith, Corinne. \"Historic American Engineering Record Cotter Bridge (R.M. Ruthven Bridge).\" 1988. [http://www.arkansashighways.com/historic_bridge/HAER%20Documents/AR-15%20Cotter%20Bridge%20(00702).pdf History.] Page 6. Retrieved August 20, 2010.</ref> Arkansas did not have a central highway body at the time, and was instead a patchwork of [[Transportation of Arkansas#The \"district approach\" dooms hopes of unity|\"road districts\"]], which made the bridge-building efforts even more difficult. Without a toll, funding wasn't available until [[Arkansas Highway 12]] was redesignated [[U.S. Route 62]] in 1930. The [[Cotter Bridge]] was constructed through the area using a unique rainbow arch design.\n\n==Geography==\nCotter is located at {{coord|36|16|29|N|92|31|42|W|type:city}} (36.274772, -92.528336).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|2.5|sqmi|km2}}, all land.\n\n=== Transportation ===\n\n==== List of highways ====\n*[[Image:US 62 (1961).svg|20px]][[Image:US 412.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Route 62 in Arkansas|US 62]]/[[U.S. Route 412 in Arkansas|US 412]]\n*[[File:US 62B.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Route 62 Business (Mountain Home, Arkansas)|U.S. Route 62 Business]]\n*[[Image:Arkansas 345.svg|24px]] [[Arkansas Highway 345]]\n\n==== Railroads ====\nCotter has one local railroad, the Missouri and Northern Arkansas Railroad. The MNA leases the track from [[Newport, Arkansas|Newport]] to [[Kansas City, Missouri]], from the [[Union Pacific Railroad|Union Pacific]]. The regular train traffic are empty coal trains from The Independence power plant, as well as a north and south local out of Cotter.\n\n==== Airports ====\nCotter is accessible to two separate commercial airports, Ozark Regional Airport (Baxter County) and Flippin Municipal Airport \n(Marion County). There is also a rural air field, Valley Airport, located on Denton Ferry Road that serves small planes owned by residents.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1910= 894\n|1920= 884\n|1930= 1064\n|1940= 903\n|1950= 1089\n|1960= 683\n|1970= 858\n|1980= 920\n|1990= 867\n|2000= 921\n|2010= 970\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=942\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=February 22, 2020}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=U.S. Census website }}</ref> of 2010, there were 1,078 people, 472 households and 293 families residing in the city.  The [[population density]] was 373.6 people per square mile (144.0/km\u00b2).  There were 501 housing units at an average density of 203.2 per square mile (78.3/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the city was 97.07% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 0.87% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 0.22% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], and 1.85% from two or more races.  1.52% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 545<ref name=\"American Fact Finder\">{{cite web | url=https://www.census.gov | title=2010 Census Results | accessdate=April 9, 2011}}</ref> households out of which 20.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 48.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 8.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 40.0% were non-families. 35.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 16.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.08 and the average family size was 2.67.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 19.7% under the age of 18, 8.7% from 18 to 24, 24.8% from 25 to 44, 26.7% from 45 to 64, and 20.2% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 43 years. For every 100 females, there were 97.2 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 99.5 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $22,857, and the median income for a family was $34,375. Males had a median income of $26,298 versus $17,266 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $15,893.  About 11.9% of families and 16.8% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 18.3% of those under age 18 and 13.3% of those age 65 or over.\n\n== Education ==\nPublic education is provided by the Cotter School District including [[Cotter High School (Cotter, Arkansas)|Cotter High School]] (grades 7 through 12) and Amanda Gist Elementary School (kindergarten through grade 6).<ref>{{Cite map\n  |publisher = US Census Bureau\n  |title = School District Reference Map (2010 Census) Baxter County, AR\n  |url = http://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/dc10map/sch_dist/st05_ar/c05005_baxter/DC10SD_C05005_001.pdf\n  |accessdate = 2011-07-12 }}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www2.census.gov/geo/pvs/bas/bas11/st05_ar/incplace/p0515490_cotter/BAS11P10500015490_001.pdf Map of Cotter] (US Census Bureau)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121019104620/http://www2.census.gov/geo/pvs/bas/bas11/st05_ar/cou/c05005_baxter/BAS11C20500500000_000.pdf Map of Baxter County] (US Census Bureau)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100528153130/http://www.baxtercountyhistory.org/ Baxter County Historical and Genealogical Society]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Baxter County, Arkansas}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Baxter County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Cities in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1905]]\n", "name_user": "Willardharris819", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a notable person", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cotter,_Arkansas"}
{"title_page": "Military history of Bangladesh", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Armor at Bangladesh Military Museum.jpg|thumb|Medieval armor preserved in the Bangladesh Military Museum]]\n[[Bangladesh]]'s [[military history]] is intertwined with the history of a larger region, including present-day [[Military history of India|India]], [[Military history of Pakistan|Pakistan]], [[Military history of Nepal|Nepal]], [[Military history of Bhutan|Bhutan]] and [[Military history of Myanmar|Myanmar]]. The country was historically part of Bengal\u2013 a major medieval power in [[South Asia]] and [[Southeast Asia]].\n\nMuslims brought new military technology to the region after the 12th century. According to [[Jo\u00e3o de Barros]], Bengal enjoyed military supremacy over [[Arakan]] and [[Kingdom of Tripura|Tripura]] due to good [[artillery]].<ref name=\"banglapedia1\">{{cite web|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Military |title=Military - Banglapedia |publisher=En.banglapedia.org |date= |accessdate=27 September 2017}}</ref> Its forces possessed large guns and [[cannons]]. It was also a major exporter of [[gunpowder]] and [[saltpeter]] to Europe.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{Cite web |url=http://archive.dhakatribune.com/heritage/2014/nov/01/gunpowder-plots |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929135203/http://archive.dhakatribune.com/heritage/2014/nov/01/gunpowder-plots |archive-date=29 September 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>[http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Saltpetre Saltpetre - Banglapedia<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Bengal had a cosmopolitan military, including [[Muslims]], [[Hindus]], [[Buddhists]] and [[mercenaries]] from Africa, [[Central Asia|Central]] and West Asia. The [[Bengal Sultanate]] was a powerful kingdom between the 14th and 15th centuries. Bengal became an integral part of the [[Mughal Empire]] in the 16th century. The [[Mughal Army]] built [[fortifications]] across the region and expelled Arakanese and Portuguese [[pirate]]s from the northeastern coastline of the [[Bay of Bengal]]. Throughout the [[late medieval]] and [[early modern]] periods, Bengal was notable for its [[navy]] and [[Shipbuilding in Bangladesh|shipbuilding]]. Its shipyards produced ships for the Mughal, Ottoman and British navies.\n\nA [[Bengal Army]] was established by the [[British East India Company]] in 1756, including native and European infantry. The native infantry included [[Bengalis]], [[Punjabis]] and [[Gurkhas]]. The Bengal Army was merged into the [[British Indian Army]] after the [[Indian Rebellion of 1857]]. The British Indian Army participated in [[World War I]] and [[World War II]]. Bengali veterans of the [[Burma Campaign]] served in the [[Pakistan Armed Forces]] after the [[partition of India]]. Amid the [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] and a [[1971 Bangladesh genocide|genocide]] by West Pakistan in 1971, the [[Military of Bangladesh|Bangladeshi military]] was formed by defecting regiments in [[East Pakistan]], led by the [[East Bengal Regiment]]. The guerrilla [[Mukti Bahini]] played an important role during the war of independence. In the late 1970s and 1980s, the Bangladeshi military saw several [[Military coups in Bangladesh|insurrections]] as the country endured [[dictatorship]]. Since the restoration of [[parliamentary democracy]] in 1991, the Bangladesh Armed Forces have been subordinate to the civilian governments, including political and technocratic governments.\n\nSince contributing forces to the [[First Gulf War]] in 1991, Bangladesh has become a major contributor in [[UN Peacekeeping]]. Bangladeshi peacekeepers have served in the [[Balkans]], [[Africa]], the [[Middle East]] and the [[Caribbean]]. Its recent domestic military history has focused on [[counter-insurgency]], [[counter-terrorism]] and [[maritime security]] operations. \n\nThe [[2008 Bangladesh\u2013Myanmar naval standoff]] was a notable event of modern Bangladeshi military history.\n\n==Early history==\n===Pre-Islamic Era===\nThe early [[military history of India|military history of the Indian subcontinent]] included [[Alexander's invasion of India]], which was deterred by the might of Gangaridai Kingdom that was located in present-day Bangladesh, according to most historians. [[Prince Vijaya]] of the [[Vanga Kingdom]] led a naval expedition to conquer Sri Lanka. The [[Kalinga War]] was a notable event of the [[Mauryan Empire]] in the eastern Indian subcontinent. The ancient Indian armies included [[chariot]]s. \n\n===Pala period===\nThe Bengal region crystallized as an imperial power during the 8th-11th century [[Pala Empire]]. Many of the empire's cities are located in Bangladesh. The Pala military had a large [[war elephant]] cavalry, according to [[Arab people|Arab]] historians. The Palas recruited mercenaries from different parts of the Indian subcontinent. Pala conquests extended across North India. The Palas were engaged in a struggle over the [[Kannauj]] Triangle with the [[Gurjara-Pratihara]]s and [[Rashtrakuta]]s.\n  \n===Sultanate period===\nThe [[Muslim conquest of the Indian subcontinent]] heralded new military doctrines and hardware, including well-developed [[artillery]]. The [[Delhi Sultanate]] conquered Bengal in 1204 under the leadership of Bakhtiar Khilji, who later proceeded with an [[Islamic invasion of Tibet]]. In Bengal, the Delhi Sultanate displaced the [[Sena dynasty]]. Sultan Iwas Khilji (1212-1227) was responsible for founding the Bengal [[navy]] during the sultanate period.<ref name=\"banglapedia1\"/> The chief of the [[admiralty]] had various responsibilities, including shipbuilding, transporting personnel, elephants and equipment; recruitment and collecting tolls at [[ghat]]s.<ref name=\"banglapedia1\"/> The sultanate period saw the settlement of many military officers and soldiers from North India, Central and West Asia and the Horn of Africa. The settlers included [[Rajputs]] and [[Pashtuns]]. \n\nIn the 14th century, Sultan [[Shamsuddin Firoz Shah]] and [[Hazrat Shah Jalal]] conquered [[Sylhet]] from Raja Gour Govinda;<ref>Muhammad Mojlum Khan (21 October 2013). The Muslim Heritage of Bengal: The Lives, Thoughts and Achievements of Great Muslim Scholars, Writers and Reformers of Bangladesh and West Bengal. Kube Publishing Limited. pp. 25. {{ISBN|978-1-84774-062-5}}.</ref> Sultan [[Fakhruddin Mubarak Shah]] conquered [[Chittagong]] from the [[Kingdom of Tripura]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Fakhruddin_Mubarak_Shah |title=Fakhruddin Mubarak Shah - Banglapedia |publisher=En.banglapedia.org |date=5 May 2014 |accessdate=27 September 2017}}</ref> [[Shamsuddin Ilyas Shah]] became known as the ''Alexander'' of the eastern subcontinent after sacking [[Kathmandu]], [[Varanasi]] and [[Cuttack]].\n\n====Bengal Sultanate====\n[[File:Bengal Sultanate.png|thumb|The [[Bengal Sultanate]]]]\nThe [[Bengal Sultanate]] was a [[List of medieval great powers|medieval great power]] and conducted a number of notable campaigns, including the [[Bengal Sultanate-Delhi Sultanate War]], the [[Bengal Sultanate-Jaunpur Sultanate War]], the [[Reconquest of Arakan]], the [[Bengal Sultanate-Kamata Kingdom War]] and the [[Bengal Sultanate-Kingdom of Mrauk U War of 1512-1516]]. The naval strength of Bengal was notable during the [[Ilyas Shahi dynasty]] and the [[Hussain Shahi dynasty]].<ref name=\"banglapedia1\"/>\n\n====Invasion of Sher Shah====\n[[File:Bibi Mariam.jpg|thumb|The [[Bibi Mariam Cannon]]]]\n[[Sher Shah Suri]] conquered Bengal in the 16th century and made it part of the [[Suri Empire]]. Sher Shah Suri also renovated the [[Grand Trunk Road]] around [[Sonargaon]]. His successors later revived the Bengal Sultanate. \n\n====Isa Khan's campaigns====\nAfter the Bengal Sultanate collapsed in the late 16th-century, the aristocrat [[Isa Khan]] led a confederation of [[zamindar]]s (known as [[Baro-Bhuyan]]) to challenge the [[Mughal invasion of Bengal]], often with [[naval]] battles on the [[Padma River]], [[Meghna River]] and [[Jangalbari Fort]] in [[Egarasindhur]]. Isa Khan defeated Mughal governors [[Khan Jahan I]] in 1578, [[Shahbaz Khan Kamboh|Shahbaz Khan]] in 1584 and [[Man Singh I]] in 1594. His son and successor [[Musa Khan]] continued to lead the confederation until succumbing to the Mughals led by [[Islam Khan I]] in 1610.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Isa_Khan |title=Isa Khan - Banglapedia |publisher=En.banglapedia.org |date=5 May 2014 |accessdate=27 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Mughal period===\n[[File:Ottoman fleet Indian Ocean 16th century.jpg|thumb|upright|During the 17th century, Ottoman navy vessels were built in Bangladesh]]\nBengal remained relatively stable and prosperous during the 17th century. A key challenge during the early Mughal period was [[piracy]] from the [[Kingdom of Mrauk U]] and the [[Portuguese settlement in Chittagong]]. In 1666, the Mughal Empire-Kingdom of Mrauk U War expelled the Arakanese and Portuguese from [[Chittagong]]. The Mughals also engaged in the [[Ahom-Mughal conflicts]]. During the 18th century, Bengal endured the [[Maratha invasions of Bengal|invasions]] by the [[Maratha Army]]- the military of the [[Maratha Confederacy]]. It fell to the conquest of the [[British East India Company]] after the [[Battle of Plassey]].\n\n===Forts===\nMud forts were common in Bengal, such as the Ekdala Fort used in the [[Bengal Sultanate-Delhi Sultanate War]]. By the 17th century, the Mughals constructed a series of riverside fortifications in the Bengal delta. Some of the surviving forts include the following.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Fort |title=Fort - Banglapedia |publisher=En.banglapedia.org |date=13 April 2015 |accessdate=27 September 2017}}</ref> \n*[[Mahasthangarh]]\n*[[Idrakpur Fort]]\n*[[Sonakanda Fort]]\n*[[Hajiganj Fort]]\n*[[Lalbagh Fort]]\n*[[Jangalbari Fort]]\n\n===Artillery===\n[[File:Lalbag Fort Museum Rezowan3.jpg|thumb|Guns preserved in the [[Lalbagh Fort]] Museum]]\nThe artillery was a vital part of the Bengal military. The Mughal emperor [[Babur]] saw it as a very effective part of the Bengal army. Portuguese historian [[Jo\u00e3o de Barros]] opined that the military supremacy of the Bengal army over that of Arakan and Tripura was due to the efficiency of its artillery. The artillery used [[cannon]]s and [[gun]]s of various sizes.<ref>[http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Military Military - Banglapedia<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The [[Bibi Mariam Cannon]] and the [[Jahan Kosha Cannon]] are examples of early modern Bengali artillery. \n\nBengal was a major exporter of [[gunpowder]] and [[saltpeter]] to Europe until the 19th century.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\n===Mercenaries===\nForeign mercenaries were an important part of the Bengal Sultanate army. Bengal recruited mercenaries from [[Abyssinia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/bengal |title=BENGAL \u2013 Encyclopaedia Iranica |publisher=Iranicaonline.org |date= |accessdate=27 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Shipbuilding===\n{{See also|Shipbuilding in Bangladesh}}\nIn the 14th century, [[Ibn Battuta]] reported of large fleets of war boats in the Bengal Sultanate. According to the traveler Frederick Caesar, [[Chittagong]] was a leading shipbuilding center in the 15th century. During the 17th century, the shipyards of Chittagong were reported to have built an entire fleet of warships for the [[Ottoman navy]]. During the [[Mughal Empire]], Bengal was the leading producer ships in the subcontinent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Shipbuilding_Industry |title=Shipbuilding Industry - Banglapedia |publisher=En.banglapedia.org |date=14 December 2014 |accessdate=27 September 2017}}</ref> \n\nThe British [[Royal Navy]] had many of its ships built in Chittagong, including vessels used in the [[Battle of Trafalgar]].\n\n==Colonial military history==\n[[File:Gravestone back view in Chittagong war cemetery.jpg|thumb|[[Commonwealth War Cemetery, Chittagong]]]]\nThe [[Bengal Army]] was formed in 1765 by the [[British East India Company]]. The first native infantry was formed in 1757.<ref name=\"banglapedia1\"/> In the 19th century, the Bengal Army was merged into the [[British Indian Army]] under the [[British Raj]]. The [[Royal Indian Navy]] was formed in 1830. The Royal Indian Air Force was formed in 1932. The [[Bangladesh Armed Forces]] were raised from the armed forces of the British Raj, which included the [[Bengal Regiment]] and major installations such as the [[Dhaka Cantonment]], [[Chittagong Cantonment]] and the [[Majhira Cantonment|Bogra Cantonment]].The following includes a list of conflicts which occurred within the territory of Bangladesh under British rule.  \n*[[Siege of Calcutta]], attempt by the last Nawab of Bengal to recapture [[Fort William (India)|Fort William]] from the [[East India Company]]\n*[[Battle of Plassey]]- defection of [[Mir Jafar]] causes defeat of [[Siraj-ud-Daulah]], the last independent Nawab of Bengal \n*[[Anglo-Nepalese War]]- leads to Treaty of Sugali with [[Kingdom of Nepal|Nepal]] and [[Treaty of Titalia]] (signed in [[Tetulia Upazila|Tetulia]]) with [[Kingdom of Sikkim|Sikkim]] \n*[[First Anglo-Burmese War]]- Burmese forces invade [[Chittagong Division]] \n*[[Indian Rebellion of 1857]]- includes revolt by the Bengal Army in Dhaka, Chittagong and Sylhet\n*[[Bhutan War]]- Bhutan loses control of [[Bengal Duars]], including parts of [[Panchagarh District]] \n*[[Burma Campaign]]- [[Allied Forces of World War II]] stationed in [[Chittagong]], [[Comilla]], [[Dhaka]] and [[Sylhet]]; [[Imperial Japanese Air Force]] bombs Chittagong \n\nThere was strong opposition to British involvement against the [[Turkish War of Independence]], as both [[Mustafa Kemal Ataturk]] and the Ottoman caliphate enjoyed support in Bengal. \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background:red; color:white;\"| '''Name of Conflict'''\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:red; color:white;\"|'''Belligerents'''\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background:red; color:white;\"| '''Outcome'''\n|-\n!  style=\"width:200px; background:red; color:white;\"|'''''Allies'''''\n!  style=\"width:200px; background:red; color:white;\"| '''''Opponent(s)'''''\n|-\n|'''[[Second Opium War]]'''<br>(1856&ndash;1860)\n|{{flagicon|United Kingdom|size=25px}} [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British Empire]]\n*{{flag|United Kingdom|size=25px}}\n*{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n{{flagicon|France|size=25px}} [[Second French Empire|French Empire]]\n|{{flag|Qing dynasty|size=25px}}\n|'''Victory'''\n*[[Treaties of Tientsin]].\n|-\n|'''[[Ambela Campaign]]'''<br>(1863&ndash;1864)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|Afghan [[Pashtun people|Pashtuns]]<br />[[Yusufzai]] tribes\n||'''Victory'''\n*Bunerwals surrender.\n*Malka burned.\n|-\n|'''[[Bhutan War]]'''<br>(1864&ndash;1865)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|[[File:Flag of Bhutan (1949-1956).svg|25px|border]] [[Bhutan]]\n||'''Victory'''\n*Bhutanese territorial cessions to India.\n|-\n|'''[[British Expedition to Abyssinia]]'''<br>(1867&ndash;1868)\n|{{flagicon|United Kingdom|size=25px}} [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]\n*{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|[[File:Flag_of_Ethiopia_(1897-1936;_1941-1974).svg|25px|border]] [[Ethiopian Empire]]\n||'''Victory'''\n*British victory at the Battle of Magdala, Theodore II commits suicide.\n|-\n|'''[[Second Anglo-Afghan War]]'''<br>(1878&ndash;1880)\n|{{flagicon|United Kingdom|size=25px}} [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]\n*{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|[[Image:Flag of Afghanistan pre-1901.svg|25px|border]] [[Emirate of Afghanistan|Afghanistan]]\n|'''Victory'''\n*[[Treaty of Gandamak]], British objectives attained.\n*Afghanistan's tribal frontier areas annexed into British India.\n*Afghanistan becomes a British Protectorate.\n|-\n|'''[[Mahdist War]]'''<br>(1881&ndash;1899)\n|{{flagicon|United Kingdom|size=25px}} [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]\n*{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n{{flagcountry|Egypt|1882|size=25px}}<br/>[[File:Ethiopian Pennants.svg|27px]] [[Ethiopian Empire|Ethiopia]]\n|{{flagicon image|Black flag.svg|size=25px}} [[Muhammad Ahmad|Mahdist]] [[Sudan]]\n||'''Victory'''\n*Sudan became an [[Anglo-Egyptian Sudan|Anglo-Egyptian]] [[Condominium (international law)|condominium]].\n|-\n|'''[[Anglo-Egyptian War]]'''<br>(1882)\n|{{flagicon|United Kingdom|size=25px}} [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]\n*{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n[[File:Flag of Egypt (1882-1922).svg|border|25px]] [[Tewfik Pasha]]\n|[[Image:Egypt flag 1882.svg|25px|border]] [[Ahmed Orabi]]\n|'''Victory'''\n*[[Ahmed Orabi]] exiled, [[History of Egypt under the British|British occupation of Egypt]].\n|-\n|'''[[Third Anglo-Burmese War]]'''<br>(1885)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|[[File:Flag of the Alaungpaya Dynasty of Myanmar.svg|border|25px]] [[Konbaung Dynasty|Burmese Empire]]\n|'''Victory'''\n*The province of Burma became part of the [[British Raj]].\n|-\n|'''[[Third Black Mountain Expedition]]'''<br>(1888)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|[[Hassanzai]] and [[Akazai]] tribes.\n|'''Victory'''\n*Allaiwal village of Pokal occupied and destroyed.\n|-\n|'''[[Sikkim Expedition]]'''<br>(1888)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|{{flagicon|Tibet|size=25px}} [[Tibet]]\n|'''Victory'''\n*Tibetan forces expelled from [[Sikkim]].\n|-\n|'''[[Hunza-Nagar Campaign]]'''<br>(1891)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|[[Hunza (princely state)|Hunza]]<br/>[[Nagar (princely state)|Nagar]]\n|'''Victory'''\n*The British gained control of [[Hunza (princely state)|Hunza]] and [[Nagar (princely state)|Nagar]].\n|-\n|'''[[Chitral Expedition]]'''<br>(1895)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|[[Chitral]]is [[Bajour]]i and Afghan Tribesmen\n|'''Victory'''\n*Fort of Chitral relieved.\n|-\n|'''[[Anglo-Zanzibar War]]'''<br>(1896)\n|{{flagcountry|British Empire|size=25px}}\n*{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|{{flagicon image|Flag of the Sultanate of Zanzibar.svg}} [[Zanzibar Sultanate]]\n|'''Victory'''\n*End of the [[Sultanate of Zanzibar]].\n*Zanzibar ceded to the British Empire.\n|-\n|'''[[Tochi Expedition]]'''<br>(1896)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|[[Waziris]]\n|'''Victory'''\n*Rebellion put down.\n|-\n|'''[[Siege of Malakand]]'''<br>(1897)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|\u067e\u0634\u062a\u0648\u0646 [[Pashtun people|Pashtun]] tribes\n|'''Victory'''\n*Siege successful.\n|-\n|'''[[First Mohmand Campaign]]'''<br>(1897&ndash;1898)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|{{flagicon image|Black flag.svg|size=25px}} [[Mohmands]]\n|'''Victory'''\n*[[Punitive expedition]] successful.\n|-\n|'''[[Tirah Campaign]]'''<br>(1897&ndash;1898)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|[[Afridi]]s<br>[[Orakzai]]s<br>[[Chamkani (Pashtun tribe)|Chamkani]]s\n|'''Victory'''\n*Negotiations for peace were then begun with the Afridis.\n|-\n|'''[[Boxer Rebellion]]'''<br>(1899&ndash;1901)\n|{{flagicon|Empire of Japan|size=25px}} [[Empire of Japan]]<br>{{flagicon|Russian Empire|size=25px}} [[Russian Empire|Russia]]<br>{{flagicon|British Empire|size=25px}} [[British Empire|United Kingdom]]\n*{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n{{flagicon|France|size=25px}} [[French Third Republic|France]]<br>{{flag|United States|1896|size=25px}}<br>{{flagicon|German Empire|size=25px}} [[German Empire|Germany]]<br>{{flag|Austria-Hungary|size=25px}}<br>{{flagicon|Kingdom of Italy|size=25px}} [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Italy]]\n|{{flagicon image|Yihetuan flag.png|size=25px}} [[Righteous Harmony Society|Yihetuan Movement]]<br />{{flag|Qing Dynasty|size=25px|name=Qing 