l guide to citizens' rights and responsibilities'', Macmillan Reference USA/Thomson Gale, 2006, [https://books.google.com/books?ei=LZPBTMaLEsiHccev8P0C&ct=result&id=vAUWAQAAIAAJ&dq=%22Turkish+War+of+Independence%22+resulted+%22Decisive+Turkish+victory%22&q=%22Turkish+victory%22#search_anchor p. 205.]</ref>\n*Overthrow of the Ottoman Sultanate.\n*[[Armistice of Mudanya]].\n*[[Treaty of Lausanne]].\n*Establishment of the [[Turkey|Republic of Turkey]].\n|-\n|'''[[Third Anglo-Afghan War]]'''<br>(1919)\n|{{flagicon|United Kingdom|size=25px}} [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]\n*{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|[[Image:Flag of Afghanistan (1919\u20131921).svg|25px|border]] [[Emirate of Afghanistan|Afghanistan]]\n|'''Armistice'''\n*[[Anglo-Afghan Treaty of 1919|Treaty of Rawalpindi]]\n*Afghan invasion repelled.\n*Afghanistan regains control of external affairs.\n*Reaffirmation of the Durand Line.\n|-\n|'''[[Waziristan campaign (1919\u201320)|First Waziristan Campaign]]'''<br>(1919)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|[[Image:Flag of Waziristan resistance (1930s).svg|25px|border]] [[Waziristan]]\n|'''Victory'''\n*Suppression of insurrection by independent Wazir tribes.\n|-\n|'''[[Kuwait\u2013Najd War]]'''<br>(1919&ndash;1920)\n|{{flagicon|British Empire|size=25px}} [[British Empire|United Kingdom]]\n*{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n{{flagicon image|Flag of Kuwait (1915-1956).svg}} [[Kuwait]]\n|[[File:Flag of the Second Saudi State.svg|border|25px]] [[Sultanate of Nejd]]\n*[[File:Flag of Ikhwan.svg|25px]] [[Ikhwan]]\n|'''Victory'''\n*Ikhawan retreat.\n|-\n|'''[[Iraqi revolt against the British|Iraqi revolt]]'''<br>(1920)\n|{{flagicon|United Kingdom|size=25px}} [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]\n*{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|{{flagicon image|Flag_of_Hejaz_1917.svg|size=25px}} [[Iraq|Iraqi rebels]]\n|'''Victory'''\n*[[Faisal I of Iraq]] installed as the [[List of kings of Iraq|King of Iraq]].\n|-\n|'''[[Malabar rebellion]]'''<br>(1921)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|[[Mappila]] Muslims\n|'''Victory'''\n*Rebellion suppressed.\n|-\n|'''[[Pink's War]]'''<br>(1925)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|[[Mahsud|Mahsud tribesmen]]\n|'''Victory'''\n*Tribal leaders accept terms.\n|-\n|'''[[Second Mohmand Campaign]]'''<br>(1935)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|{{flagicon image|Black flag.svg|size=25px}} [[Mohmands]]\n|'''Victory'''\n*[[Jirga]] and peace.\n|-\n|'''[[Waziristan campaign (1936\u201339)|Second Waziristan Campaign]]'''<br>(1936&ndash;1939)\n|{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|[[Image:Flag of Waziristan resistance (1930s).svg|25px|border]] [[Waziristan|Waziri tribesmen]]\n|'''Victory'''\n*Suppression of insurrection by independent Wazir tribes.\n|-\n|'''[[World War II]]'''<br>(1939&ndash;1945)\n|{{flag|Soviet Union|1923|size=25px}}<br>\n{{flag|United States|1912|size=25px}}<br>\n{{flag|United Kingdom|size=25px}}\n*{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n{{flagcountry|Republic of China|size=25px}}<br />\n{{flagcountry|Union of South Africa|1928|size=25px}}<br />\n{{flag|Australia|size=25px}}<br />\n{{flag|Canada|1868|size=25px}}<br />\n{{flag|New Zealand|size=25px}}<br />\n{{flag|France|size=25px}}<br />{{flag|Poland|size=25px}}<br/>{{flagcountry|Democratic Federal Yugoslavia|size=25px}}<br />{{flagcountry|Kingdom of Greece|size=25px}}<br />{{flag|Denmark|size=25px}}<br />{{flag|Norway|size=25px}}<br />{{flag|Netherlands|size=25px}}<br />{{flag|Belgium|size=25px}}<br />{{flag|Luxembourg|size=25px}}<br />{{flagcountry|Czechoslovakia|size=25px}}\n|{{flagcountry|Nazi Germany|1935|size=25px}}\n*{{flag|Vichy France|size=25px}}\n{{flagcountry|Kingdom of Italy|size=25px}}<br />\n{{flagcountry|Empire of Japan|size=25px}}\n*{{flag|Manchukuo|size=25px}}\n*[[File:Flag of the Mengjiang.svg|25px|border]] [[Mengjiang]]\n*[[File:Flag_of_the_Republic_of_China-Nanjing_(Peace,_Anti-Communism,_National_Construction).svg|25px|border]] [[Wang Jingwei regime]]\n*{{flagicon|India|1931|size=25px}} [[Arzi Hukumat-e-Azad Hind|Azad Hind]]\n*{{flag|Thailand|size=25px}}\n*[[File:Old Flag Of Vietnam.svg|25px|border]] [[Empire of Vietnam]]\n*[[File:Flag of the State of Burma (1943-45).svg|25px|border]] [[State of Burma]]\n{{flagcountry|Kingdom of Hungary|size=25px}} <br />{{flagcountry|Kingdom of Romania|size=25px}} <br />{{flagcountry|Kingdom of Bulgaria|size=25px}}\n|'''Victory'''\n* Collapse of the [[Nazi Germany|German Reich]]\n* Collapse of [[Fascism]] in Italy\n* Creation of the [[United Nations]]\n* Emergence of the [[United States]] and the [[Soviet Union]] as [[superpower]]s\n* Beginning of the [[Cold War]]\n|-\n|'''[[Indonesian National Revolution]]'''<br>(1945&ndash;1947)\n|{{flagicon|Netherlands|size=25px}} [[Netherlands]]<br/>{{flagicon|United Kingdom|size=25px}} [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]\n*{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n|{{flagicon|Indonesia|size=25px}} [[Indonesia]]\n|'''Withdrawal'''\n*Indian withdrawal after independence in 1947.\n*The [[Netherlands]] recognises Indonesian independence.\n|-\n|'''[[War in Vietnam (1945\u201346)|Operation Masterdom]]'''<br>(1945&ndash;1946)\n|{{flagicon|United Kingdom|size=25px}} [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]\n*{{flagcountry|British Raj|size=25px}}\n{{flagicon|France|size=25px}} [[Provisional Government of the French Republic|France]]<br>{{flagicon|Japan|size=25px}} [[Occupation of Japan|Japan]]\n|[[File:Flag_of_North_Vietnam_(1945-1955).svg|25px|border]] [[Viet Minh]]\n|'''Withdrawal'''\n*Start of the [[First Indochina War]], lasting until the [[Geneva Conference (1954)|Geneva Conference]] of 1954.\n|}\n\n==Eastern wing of Pakistan==\n{{See also|East Bengal Regiment}}\nWith the [[partition of India]] on 15 August 1947 the territory constituting modern Bangladesh was [[1947 Partition of Bengal|partitioned]] from the province of [[Bengal]] as [[East Bengal]], joining the newly created state of Pakistan. Ethnic and sectional discrimination hampered the role and function of the Pakistani military. Bengalis were under-represented in the Pakistan military. Officers of Bengali origin in the different wings of the armed forces made up just 5% of overall force by 1965.<ref name=\"Library\">{{cite book |date=1989 |editor1-last=Heitzman |editor1-first=James |editor2-last=Worden |editor2-first=Robert |chapter=Pakistan Era |title=Bangladesh: A Country Study |chapter-url=https://www.loc.gov/item/89600298/ |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Federal Research Division, Library of Congress |page=207}}</ref> West Pakistanis believed that Bengalis were not \"martially inclined\" unlike [[Pashtun people|Pashtuns]] and [[Punjabi people|Punjabis]]; the \"[[Martial Race]]s\" notion was dismissed as ridiculous and humiliating by Bengalis.<ref name=\"Library\" /> Moreover, despite huge defence spending, East Pakistan received none of the benefits, such as contracts, purchasing and military support jobs. The [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1965]] over [[Kashmir]] also highlighted the sense of military insecurity among Bengalis as only an under-strength [[infantry]] division and 15 [[combat aircraft]] without [[tank]] support were in East Pakistan to thwart any Indian retaliations during the conflict.<ref>[http://www.defencejournal.com/2002/dec/demons.htm Demons of December \u2014 Road from East Pakistan to Bangladesh]</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Jahan |first=Rounaq |author-link=Rounaq Jahan |date=1972 |title=Pakistan: Failure in National Integration |publisher=Columbia University Press |pages=166\u2013167 |isbn=0-231-03625-6}}</ref>\n\n[[Khwaja Wasiuddin]] was the most senior Bengali officer in the Pakistani military. \n==Bangladesh Liberation War==\n{{Main|Bangladesh Liberation War}}\n[[File:March71.PNG|thumb|Location of Bengali and Pakistani military units in March 1971]]\n[[File:Bangladesh Military Museum - 3.7 inch howitzer.jpg|thumb|[[QF 3.7-inch mountain howitzer]]s used by the [[Mukti Bahini]]]]\nFollowing the victory of the [[Awami League]] in the 1970 elections, then-president General [[Yahya Khan]] refused to appoint its leader [[Sheikh Mujibur Rahman]] as the [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|prime minister]] and launched a brutal attack named ''[[Operation Searchlight]]'' on the civilians of the then East Pakistan, using the Pakistani army to repress political movements.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Bose |first=Sarmila |date=8 October 2005 |title=Anatomy of Violence: Analysis of Civil War in East Pakistan in 1971 |url=http://www.epw.org.in/showArticles.php?root=2005&leaf=10&filename=9223&filetype=html |journal=[[Economic and Political Weekly]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070301084941/http://www.epw.org.in/showArticles.php?root=2005&leaf=10&filename=9223&filetype=html |archive-date=1 March 2007}}</ref> Figures of people killed by Pakistani forces vary from a minimum of around 300,000 to a maximum of around 3&nbsp;million.<ref name=MathewWhite>Matthew White's ''[http://users.erols.com/mwhite28/warstat2.htm#Bangladesh Death Tolls for the Major Wars and Atrocities of the Twentieth Century]''</ref><ref>[http://www.virtualbangladesh.com/history/holocaust.html Virtual Bangladesh : History : The Bangali Genocide, 1971] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723203401/http://www.virtualbangladesh.com/history/holocaust.html |date=23 July 2011 }}</ref> Responding to Mujib's call for rebellion, many students, workers and other civilians mutinied against Pakistan and raised the [[Mukti Bahini]], a [[guerrilla]] force. Later on, many Bengali officers and units from [[Pakistan Army]] and [[East Pakistan Rifles]] mutinied against their West Pakistani counterparts and joined the Mukti bahini.<ref name=\"Rule\">{{cite book |date=1989 |editor1-last=Heitzman |editor1-first=James |editor2-last=Worden |editor2-first=Robert |chapter=Zia's regime |chapter-url=http://countrystudies.us/bangladesh/21.htm |title=Bangladesh: A Country Study |url=http://countrystudies.us/bangladesh/ |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Federal Research Division, Library of Congress |pages=37\u201340}}</ref><ref name=\"UB\">{{cite book |last=Ahmed |first=Helal Uddin |year=2012 |chapter=Mukti Bahini |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Mukti_Bahini |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref><ref name=\"II\">{{cite book |last=Uddin |first=Syed Mohd. Saleh |year=2012 |chapter=Bangladesh Air Force |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Bangladesh_Air_Force |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref> On 17 April 1971, [[Muhammad Ataul Gani Osmani]] took oath as the commander-in-chief of Mukti bahini. While the war raged on, the necessity of a well-trained armed force was always felt. During the first Bangladesh Sector Commanders Conference, held from 11 to 17 July 1971, the [[Bangladesh Forces]] was formed from the revolting Bengali members of the Pakistan Army and EPR.<ref name=\"bengalrenaissance1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bengalrenaissance.com/war.html|title=Bangladesh War of Independence. The history of Bangladesh Independence War.|last=Kawakita|first=Atsuyo|website=www.bengalrenaissance.com|access-date=2017-10-03}}</ref> In this historic conference the field command structure, sector reorganization, reinforcement, appointment of field commanders and tactics of warfare were decided upon and carried out. On 21 November 1971, the Bangladesh Forces was divided into three separate services as [[Bangladesh Army]], [[Bangladesh Navy]] and [[Bangladesh Air Force]].\n\nThe Bangladesh Forces received modest assistance from the Indian Government soon after the start of the war.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/op-ed/politics/unfinished-agenda-the-liberation-war-1199692|title=Unfinished agenda of the Liberation War|date=2016-03-26|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2017-10-03|language=en}}</ref> On 3 December 1971, India-Pakistan war broke out and Indian troops enter Bangladesh allied with the Bangladesh Armed Forces.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/supplements/independence-day-special-2015/the-tangail-landings-signal-victory-73754|title=The Tangail Landings: A signal for victory|date=2015-03-26|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2017-10-03|language=en}}</ref> On 16 December 1971 the Pakistani Military force in Bangladesh surrender to a joint force of Indian and Bangladesh forces.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-261277|title=Witnessing the surrender|date=2012-12-16|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2017-10-03|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Post-independence==\n{{See also|Military coups in Bangladesh|Chittagong Hill Tracts Conflict}}\nThe newly formed Bangladeshi armed forces incorporated some of the units and guerrillas of the Mukti Bahini.<ref name=\"LC\">{{cite book |date=1989 |editor1-last=Heitzman |editor1-first=James |editor2-last=Worden |editor2-first=Robert |chapter=Postindependence Period |title=Bangladesh: A Country Study |chapter-url=https://www.loc.gov/item/89600298/ |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Federal Research Division, Library of Congress |page=211}}</ref> Gen. Osmani, who had led the Mukti Bahini was appointed the [[Military of Bangladesh|General of the Bangladesh armed forces]].<ref name=\"OT\">{{cite book |last=Khan |first=Muazzam Hussain |year=2012 |chapter=Osmany, General Mohammad Ataul Ghani |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Osmany,_General_Mohammad_Ataul_Ghani |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref> For many years, there was active discrimination in favour of the inductees from the Mukti Bahini against those Bengali officers who had continued service in the Pakistani armed forces or had been detained in [[West Pakistan]].<ref name=\"LC\"/><ref name=\"GF\">{{cite book |date=1989 |editor1-last=Heitzman |editor1-first=James |editor2-last=Worden |editor2-first=Robert |chapter=Mujib coup |chapter-url=http://countrystudies.us/bangladesh/19.htm |title=Bangladesh: A Country Study |url=http://countrystudies.us/bangladesh/ |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Federal Research Division, Library of Congress |pages=32\u201336}}</ref> A group of angered officers [[Assassination of Sheikh Mujibur Rahman|assassinated]] the president Sheikh Mujib on 15 August 1975 and established a regime with politician [[Khondaker Mostaq Ahmed]] as [[President of Bangladesh]] and new [[Chief of Army Staff of the Bangladesh Army|army chief]] Maj. Gen. [[Ziaur Rahman]].<ref name=\"GF\"/> The military itself was subject of divisions as Mujib's assassins were overthrown by the pro-Mujib Brig. Gen. [[Khaled Mosharraf]] on 3 November, who himself was soon overthrown by a socialist group of officers under Col. [[Abu Taher]] on 7 November who returned Ziaur Rahman to power\u2014an event now called the ''[[National Revolution and Solidarity Day|Sipoy-Janata Biplob]]'' (''Soldiers and People's Coup'').<ref name=\"JSTOR3\">{{cite journal\n|last = Islam\n|first = Syed Serajul\n|date = May 1984\n|title = The State in Bangladesh under Zia (1975\u201381)\n|journal = Asian Survey\n|publisher = University of California Press\n|volume = 24\n|issue = 5\n|pages = 556\u2013573\n|jstor = 2644413\n|doi=10.1525/as.1984.24.5.01p0162r\n}}</ref> Under the presidency of Ziaur Rahman, the military was reorganised to remove conflicts between rival factions and discontented cadre.<ref name=\"VS\">{{cite book |date=1989 |editor1-last=Heitzman |editor1-first=James |editor2-last=Worden |editor2-first=Robert |chapter=Restoration of Military Rule |chapter-url=http://countrystudies.us/bangladesh/20.htm |title=Bangladesh: A Country Study |url=http://countrystudies.us/bangladesh/ |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Federal Research Division, Library of Congress |pages=36\u201337}}</ref> However, Ziaur Rahman was himself overthrown in a [[Assassination of Ziaur Rahman|1981 coup attempt]],<ref name=\"killing\">{{cite magazine\n|title = Bangladesh: Death at Night\n|url = http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,922557,00.html\n|magazine = [[Time (magazine)|Time]]\n|date = 8 June 1981\n|access-date = 10 September 2006\n|url-access=subscription\n}}</ref> and a year later, Lt. Gen. [[Hossain Mohammad Ershad]] took power from the elected government of president [[Abdus Sattar (president)|Abdus Sattar]]. The military remained the most important force in national politics under the regimes of Ziaur Rahman and later Hossain Mohammad Ershad until democracy was restored in 1991.<ref name=\"VS\"/>\n\n==Modern period==\n{{See also|Bangladesh UN Peacekeeping Force}}\n[[File:Bdunmsn3.jpg|thumb|Bangladeshi peacekeepers in [[Darfur]], [[Sudan]]]]\nHaving relied primarily on India and [[Soviet Union]] for military aid, Bangladesh has also developed military ties with the People's Republic of China and the United States. The Bangladesh Army has been actively involved in United Nations Peace Support Operations (UNPSO). During the first [[Gulf War]] in 1991, the Bangladesh Army sent a 2,193 member team to monitor peace in [[Saudi Arabia]] and [[Kuwait]]. The Bangladesh Army also participated in peace keeping activities in [[Namibia]], [[Cambodia]], [[Somalia]], [[Uganda]], [[Rwanda]], [[Mozambique]], former [[Yugoslavia]], [[Liberia]], [[Haiti]], [[Tajikistan]], [[Western Sahara]], [[Sierra Leone]], [[Kosovo]], Georgia, [[East Timor]], [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Congo]], [[C\u00f4te d'Ivoire]] and [[Ethiopia]]. As of October 2008, Bangladesh remained the second largest contributor with 9,800 troops in the UN Peacekeeping forces.\n\nUntil a peace accord was signed in 1997, the Bangladeshi military engaged in [[counterinsurgency]] operations in the [[Chittagong Hill Tracts]] fighting the [[Shanti Bahini]] separatist group. In 2001, Bangladeshi military units [[2001 Indian-Bangladeshi border conflict|engaged in clashes]] with the Indian [[Border Security Force]] (BSF) along the northern border.<ref name=\"IBG\">{{cite news |title=India-Bangladesh border conflict |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/1283068.stm |date=18 April 2001 |work=BBC News}}</ref> Controversy also emerged over possible links maintained by the Bangladeshi military and intelligence agencies with Islamic terrorist groups and anti-India secessionist outfits.<ref name=\"ISI\">{{cite web|url=http://acdis.illinois.edu/assets/docs/257/TerrorsansFrontiersIslamicMilitancyinNorthEastIndia.pdf |title=Terror Sans Frontiers: Islamic Militancy in North East India |last=Saikia |first=Jaideep |date=July 2003 |publisher=The Program in Arms Control & Domestic and International Security at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415162345/http://acdis.illinois.edu/assets/docs/257/TerrorsansFrontiersIslamicMilitancyinNorthEastIndia.pdf |archivedate=15 April 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"V\">[http://www.rediff.com/news/2007/jan/09raman.htm ULFA, an agent for India's enemies]</ref><ref name=\"HUJI\">{{cite news |last=Parthasarathy |first=G. |date=3 November 2005 |title=The Bangladesh Challenge |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/2005/11/03/stories/2005110300721000.htm |newspaper=The Hindu Business Line |type=Opinion}}</ref> Several projects and schemes aiming to expand and modernize the Bangladeshi armed forces were launched by the government of former Prime Minister [[Begum Khaleda Zia]].\n\n[[Forces Goal 2030]] was launched by the government of Prime Minister [[Sheikh Hasina]] to secure new equipment for the Bangladeshi military. \n\n===Bangladesh-Myanmar border===\nStandoffs have occasionally occurred at the [[Bangladesh-Myanmar border]], including in 1991 and 2008. Most of the standoffs took place when Myanmar attempted to force [[Rohingya people|Rohingya]]s into Bangladesh. In 2008, the two countries deployed warships after Myanmar attempted to explore a disputed Bay of Bengal seabed for oil and gas. The dispute was resolved at an international tribunal in 2012. Bangladesh and Myanmar have also conducted [[counter-insurgency]] operations on the border. \n*[[2008 Bangladesh\u2013Myanmar naval standoff]]\n*[[2015 Bangladesh-Arakan Army border clash]]\n\n==References==\n{{loc}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bangladesh topics}}\n{{Military of Bangladesh}}\n{{Asia topic|Military history of}}\n\n[[Category:Military history of Bangladesh]]\n", "name_user": "JalenFolf", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Removing link(s) to \"Europeans\":WP:OLINK. (TW))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Military_history_of_Bangladesh"}
{"title_page": "Fielding Johnson Building", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n| name       =Fielding Johnson Building\n| org/group  =\n| logo       = \n| image      =Fielding Johnson Building, University of Leicester.jpg\n| caption    =Fielding Johnson Building\n| location   =[[Leicester]]\n| region     = [[Leicestershire]]\n| state      = \n| country    = England\n| coordinates = {{coord|52.6204|-1.1278|display=inline,title}}\n| healthcare = NHS\n| type       = Specialist\n| speciality = [[Psychiatric hospital|Psychiatric]] Hospital\n| emergency  = N/A\n| affiliation= \n| beds       = \n| founded    = 1837\n| closed     = \n| website    = \n| other_links= <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   =Leicestershire\n| map_caption=Shown in Leicestershire\n}}\nThe '''Fielding Johnson Building''' is the main administrative building for the [[University of Leicester]], [[Leicester]], England. It is a Grade II [[listed building]].<ref>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1074782|desc=Fielding Johnson Building, University of Leicester|accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe building, which was designed by William Parsons with assistance from George Wallett in the late [[Georgian architecture|Georgian provincial style]] using an early Corridor Plan layout, opened as the Leicestershire and Rutland County Asylum in May 1837.<ref name=county>{{cite web|url=https://www.countyasylums.co.uk/leicestershire-county-asylum-leicester/|title=Leicester Asylum|publisher=County Asylums|accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref> There were 104 original inmates when the asylum first opened.<ref name=story>{{cite web |url=http://www.storyofleicester.info/city-heritage/built-heritage-continued/fielding-johnson-building/ |title=Fielding Johnson Building |last= Milvaques|first=Victoria |date= August 2013|publisher=Leicester City Council |website=Story Of Leicester |url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170904155226/http://www.storyofleicester.info/city-heritage/built-heritage-continued/fielding-johnson-building/|archivedate = 4 September 2017}}</ref> Both wings were extended behind the main block in 1842.<ref name=county/> After the last inmates transferred to the new [[Carlton Hayes Hospital]], the Leicester and Rutland Asylum closed in September 1908.<ref name=county/> During the [[World War I|First World War]], the building was requisitioned by the [[War Office]] to create the 5th Northern General Hospital, a facility for the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]] to treat military casualties.<ref name=county/>\n\nIn 1921 the building was acquired by [[Thomas Fielding Johnson]], a local businessman, who gifted it to [[University of Leicester|Leicestershire and Rutland University College]] on its foundation.<ref name=story/> The building was home to most of the university departments until purpose-built accommodation was created.<ref name=story/> It was renamed the Fielding Johnson Building in 1964 and has since become the main administration building of the [[University of Leicester]].<ref name=story/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Leicestershire]]\n[[Category:1837 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:1908 disestablishments in England]]\n[[Category:Former psychiatric hospitals in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n| name       =Fielding Johnson Building\n| org/group  =\n| logo       = \n| image      =Fielding Johnson Building, University of Leicester.jpg\n| caption    =Fielding Johnson Building\n| location   =[[Leicester]]\n| region     = [[Leicestershire]]\n| state      = \n| country    = England\n| coordinates = {{coord|52.6204|-1.1278|display=inline,title}}\n| healthcare = NHS\n| type       = Specialist\n| speciality = [[Psychiatric hospital|Psychiatric]] Hospital\n| emergency  = N/A\n| affiliation= \n| beds       = \n| founded    = 1837\n| closed     = \n| website    = \n| other_links= <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   =Leicestershire\n| map_caption=Shown in Leicestershire\n}}\nThe '''Fielding Johnson Building''' is the main administrative building for the [[University of Leicester]], [[Leicester]], England. It is a Grade II [[listed building]].<ref>{{National Heritage List for England|num=1074782|desc=Fielding Johnson Building, University of Leicester|accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe building, which was designed by William Parsons with assistance from George Wallett in the late [[Georgian architecture|Georgian provincial style]] using an early Corridor Plan layout, opened as the Leicestershire and Rutland County Asylum in May 1837.<ref name=county>{{cite web|url=https://www.countyasylums.co.uk/leicestershire-county-asylum-leicester/|title=Leicester Asylum|publisher=County Asylums|accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref> There were 104 original inmates when the asylum first opened.<ref name=story>{{cite web |url=http://www.storyofleicester.info/city-heritage/built-heritage-continued/fielding-johnson-building/ |title=Fielding Johnson Building |last= Milvaques|first=Victoria |date= August 2013|publisher=Leicester City Council |website=Story Of Leicester |url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170904155226/http://www.storyofleicester.info/city-heritage/built-heritage-continued/fielding-johnson-building/|archivedate = 4 September 2017}}</ref> Both wings were extended behind the main block in 1842.<ref name=county/> After the last inmates transferred to the new [[Carlton Hayes Hospital]], the Leicester and Rutland Asylum closed in September 1908.<ref name=county/> During the [[World War I|First World War]], the building was requisitioned by the [[War Office]] to create the 5th Northern General Hospital, a facility for the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]] to treat military casualties.<ref name=county/>\n\nIn 1921 the building was acquired by [[Thomas Fielding Johnson]], a local businessman, who gifted it to [[University of Leicester|Leicestershire and Rutland University College]] on its foundation.<ref name=story/> The building was home to most of the university departments until purpose-built accommodation was created.<ref name=story/> It was renamed the Fielding Johnson Building in 1964 and has since become the main administration building of the [[University of Leicester]].<ref name=story/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Defunct hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Leicestershire]]\n[[Category:1837 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:1908 disestablishments in England]]\n[[Category:Former psychiatric hospitals in England]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fielding_Johnson_Building"}
{"title_page": "Fieldhead Hospital", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n| name       = Fieldhead Hospital\n| org/group  = [[South West Yorkshire Partnership NHS Foundation Trust]]\n| logo       = \n| image      = Fieldhead Hospital - viewed from Bar Lane (geograph 3813832).jpg\n| caption    = Fieldhead Hospital\n| location   = [[Wakefield]]\n| region     = [[West Yorkshire]]\n| state      = \n| country    = England\n| coordinates = {{coord|53.6974|-1.4923|display=inline,title}}\n| healthcare = NHS\n| type       = Specialist\n| speciality = [[Psychiatric hospital|Psychiatric]] and [[Learning Disability]] Hospital\n| emergency  = N/A\n| affiliation= [[University of Huddersfield]]\n| beds       = 208\n| founded    = 1972\n| closed     = <!-- optional -->\n| website    = {{URL|http://www.southwestyorkshire.nhs.uk/}}\n| other_links= <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   =West Yorkshire\n| map_caption=Shown in West Yorkshire\n}}\n\n'''Fieldhead Hospital''' is a [[Psychiatric hospital|psychiatric]] and [[learning disability]] [[hospital]] in [[Wakefield]], [[United Kingdom]]. It is managed by [[South West Yorkshire Partnership NHS Foundation Trust]].\n\n==History==\nThe hospital, which replaced earlier hospitals such as [[Oulton Hall]], Hatfield Hall and Cardigan Hospital, was built at a cost of \u00a32 million and opened by [[Princess Alexandra, The Honourable Lady Ogilvy|Princess Alexandra]] on 11 July 1972.<ref name=park>{{cite web|url=http://www.meanwoodpark.co.uk/insight/fieldhead-hospital-wakefield/|title=Fieldhead Hospital|publisher=Meanwood Park|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref> The hospital was designed as a series of villas, each named after a local area and each intended to accommodate a category of resident i.e. children, adolescents, adults, geriatrics, or severely disabled.<ref name=park/>\n\nA medium secure unit, known as Newton Lodge, was built in the north east of the hospital site for mentally disordered offenders in the early 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.southwestyorkshire.nhs.uk/services/newton-lodge-the-yorkshire-centre-for-forensic-psychiatry/|title=Newton Lodge (The Yorkshire Centre for Forensic Psychiatry)|date=27 June 2018|publisher=South West Yorkshire Partnership NHS Foundation Trust|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe hospital started offering a broader range of psychiatric services, after the [[Stanley Royd Hospital]] closed in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/hospitalrecords/details.asp?id=705|title=Stanley Royd Hospital, Wakefield|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref> A patient suffering from [[paranoid schizophrenia]] was charged with murdering a fellow-patient at the hospital in December 1998.<ref>{{cite news|title=Health Schizophrenic man charged with hospital murder|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/239781.stm|accessdate=18 May 2015|publisher=BBC News|date=21 December 1998}}</ref>\n\nThe \"Unity Centre\", a new building with state of the art therapeutic areas, en-suite bathrooms and vastly improved patient relaxation areas, which was built at a cost of \u00a317 million, was opened in September 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/health/first-look-inside-psychiatric-hospital-after-17m-upgrade-1-8780030|title=First look inside psychiatric hospital after \u00a317m upgrade|publisher=Wakefield Express|date=29 September 2017|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Mental Health Museum==\nThe Mental Health Museum (previously known as the Stephen Beaumont Museum of Mental Health) is located at the hospital. It contains artefacts and exhibits from [[Stanley Royd Hospital]] in Wakefield.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Glimpse in the Past of a Mental Health Asylum|url=http://www.tourism-review.com/travel-tourism-magazine-uks-museum-of-mental-health-opens-the-door-of-past-article2124|publisher=Tourism Review|accessdate=18 May 2015|date=27 December 2013}}</ref> Artefacts include restraining equipment, a padded cell, photographs, medical and surgical equipment, and documents. There is also a scale model of Stanley Royd Hospital, which was the museum's original location until the hospital closed in 1995.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.medicalheritage.co.uk/YORKSHIRE.htm |title=Yorkshire & Cleveland |work=Medical Heritage of Great Britain |year=2007 |accessdate=18 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222210/http://www.medicalheritage.co.uk/YORKSHIRE.htm |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Top 10: Unusual British museums|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/picturegalleries/5540092/Top-10-Unusual-British-museums.html?image=4|accessdate=18 May 2015|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of hospitals in England]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.southwestyorkshire.nhs.uk/ Official Trust website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Psychiatric hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Museums in West Yorkshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n| name       = Fieldhead Hospital\n| org/group  = [[South West Yorkshire Partnership NHS Foundation Trust]]\n| logo       = \n| image      = Fieldhead Hospital - viewed from Bar Lane (geograph 3813832).jpg\n| caption    = Fieldhead Hospital\n| location   = [[Wakefield]]\n| region     = [[West Yorkshire]]\n| state      = \n| country    = England\n| coordinates = {{coord|53.6974|-1.4923|display=inline,title}}\n| healthcare = NHS\n| type       = Specialist\n| speciality = [[Psychiatric hospital|Psychiatric]] and [[Learning Disability]] Hospital\n| emergency  = N/A\n| affiliation= [[University of Huddersfield]]\n| beds       = 208\n| founded    = 1972\n| closed     = <!-- optional -->\n| website    = {{URL|http://www.southwestyorkshire.nhs.uk/}}\n| other_links= <!-- optional -->\n| map_type   =West Yorkshire\n| map_caption=Shown in West Yorkshire\n}}\n\n'''Fieldhead Hospital''' is a [[Psychiatric hospital|psychiatric]] and [[learning disability]] [[hospital]] in [[Wakefield]], [[United Kingdom]]. It is managed by [[South West Yorkshire Partnership NHS Foundation Trust]].\n\n==History==\nThe hospital, which replaced earlier hospitals such as [[Oulton Hall]], Hatfield Hall and Cardigan Hospital, was built at a cost of \u00a32 million and opened by [[Princess Alexandra, The Honourable Lady Ogilvy|Princess Alexandra]] on 11 July 1972.<ref name=park>{{cite web|url=http://www.meanwoodpark.co.uk/insight/fieldhead-hospital-wakefield/|title=Fieldhead Hospital|publisher=Meanwood Park|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref> The hospital was designed as a series of villas, each named after a local area and each intended to accommodate a category of resident i.e. children, adolescents, adults, geriatrics, or severely disabled.<ref name=park/>\n\nA medium secure unit, known as Newton Lodge, was built in the north east of the hospital site for mentally disordered offenders in the early 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.southwestyorkshire.nhs.uk/services/newton-lodge-the-yorkshire-centre-for-forensic-psychiatry/|title=Newton Lodge (The Yorkshire Centre for Forensic Psychiatry)|date=27 June 2018|publisher=South West Yorkshire Partnership NHS Foundation Trust|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe hospital started offering a broader range of psychiatric services, after the [[Stanley Royd Hospital]] closed in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/hospitalrecords/details.asp?id=705|title=Stanley Royd Hospital, Wakefield|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref> A patient suffering from [[paranoid schizophrenia]] was charged with murdering a fellow-patient at the hospital in December 1998.<ref>{{cite news|title=Health Schizophrenic man charged with hospital murder|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/239781.stm|accessdate=18 May 2015|publisher=BBC News|date=21 December 1998}}</ref>\n\nThe \"Unity Centre\", a new building with state of the art therapeutic areas, en-suite bathrooms and vastly improved patient relaxation areas, which was built at a cost of \u00a317 million, was opened in September 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wakefieldexpress.co.uk/news/health/first-look-inside-psychiatric-hospital-after-17m-upgrade-1-8780030|title=First look inside psychiatric hospital after \u00a317m upgrade|publisher=Wakefield Express|date=29 September 2017|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Mental Health Museum==\nThe Mental Health Museum (previously known as the Stephen Beaumont Museum of Mental Health) is located at the hospital. It contains artefacts and exhibits from [[Stanley Royd Hospital]] in Wakefield.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Glimpse in the Past of a Mental Health Asylum|url=http://www.tourism-review.com/travel-tourism-magazine-uks-museum-of-mental-health-opens-the-door-of-past-article2124|publisher=Tourism Review|accessdate=18 May 2015|date=27 December 2013}}</ref> Artefacts include restraining equipment, a padded cell, photographs, medical and surgical equipment, and documents. There is also a scale model of Stanley Royd Hospital, which was the museum's original location until the hospital closed in 1995.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.medicalheritage.co.uk/YORKSHIRE.htm |title=Yorkshire & Cleveland |work=Medical Heritage of Great Britain |year=2007 |accessdate=18 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222210/http://www.medicalheritage.co.uk/YORKSHIRE.htm |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Top 10: Unusual British museums|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/picturegalleries/5540092/Top-10-Unusual-British-museums.html?image=4|accessdate=18 May 2015|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of hospitals in England]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.southwestyorkshire.nhs.uk/ Official Trust website]\n\n[[Category:Psychiatric hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Museums in West Yorkshire]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fieldhead_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Ffestiniog Memorial Hospital", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Ffestiniog Memorial Hospital\n| Org/Group   = [[Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board]]\n| Image       = Ffestiniog WW1 Memorial Hospital, Blaenau Ffestiniog (geograph 6220104).jpg\n| image alt   = \n| Caption     = Ffestiniog Memorial Hospital\n| map_type    = Wales Gwynedd \n| map_caption = Shown in Gwynedd\n| Logo        = <!-- Please conform to copyright -->\n| Logo Size   = <!-- Use to limit the logo size -->\n| Location    = [[Blaenau Ffestiniog]]\n| Region      = [[Gwynedd]]\n| State       = <!-- optional UK: England, Wales, Scotland, Northern Ireland. US: The US State - NB autolinked -->\n| Country     = Wales\n| Coordinates = {{coord|52.9916|-3.9350|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| Address     = <!-- Address of main building -->\n| HealthCare  = [[NHS Wales]]\n| Funding     = <!-- Non-profit, For-profit, Government, Public - will generate linka -->\n| Type        = Community\n| Speciality  = \n| Standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency   = \n| Helipad     = \n| Affiliation = <!-- 'None' or Medical School and university affiliations (medical or paramedical) -->\n| Patron      = <!-- 'None' or the individual who acts as the hospital patron -->\n| Network     = <!-- Hospital network, non-owner -->\n| Beds        = \n| Founded     = 1927\n| Closed      = \n| Website     = \n| Wiki-Links  = <!-- Creates \"\"See also\" field -->\n}}\n'''Ffestiniog Memorial Hospital''' ({{lang-cy|Ysbyty Coffa Ffestiniog}}) is a health facility in [[Blaenau Ffestiniog]], [[Gwynedd]], [[Wales]]. It is managed by the [[Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board]].\n\n==History==\nThe facility, which was designed by [[Clough Williams-Ellis]], was officially opened by Colonel [[David Davies, 1st Baron Davies|David Davies]] MP as the Festiniog and District Heroes Memorial Hospital in 1927.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://player.bfi.org.uk/free/film/watch-opening-ceremony-the-festiniog-district-heroes-memorial-hospital-1927-online|title=Opening Ceremony - the Festiniog & District Heroes Memorial Hospital|publisher=British Film Institute|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> It was intended to commemorate local soldiers who had died in the [[World War I|First World War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwm.org.uk/memorials/item/memorial/24426|title=Ffestiniog Memorial Hospital|publisher=Imperial war Museum|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> After joining the [[National Health Service]] in 1948, it developed as a community hospital but, after inpatient services transferred to [[Ysbyty Alltwen]] in [[Tremadog]], it closed to inpatients in March 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/local-news/no-beds-plan-blaenau-ffestiniog-2041998|title=No beds plan for Blaenau Ffestiniog Memorial Hospital|date=14 February 2012|publisher=Wales Online|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/blaenau-memorial-hospital-closes-doors-2637960|title=Blaenau Memorial Hospital closes its doors|date=28 March 2013|publisher=Daily Post|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> It then re-opened as the Canolfan Goffa Ffestiniog (English: ''Ffestiniog Memorial Centre'') in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/new-blaenau-ffestiniog-health-centre-13911981|title=New \u00a33.9m health centre opens its doors|date=17 November 2017|publisher=Daily Post|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in Gwynedd]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1927]]\n[[Category:1927 establishments in Wales]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1927]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Ffestiniog Memorial Hospital\n| Org/Group   = [[Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board]]\n| Image       = Ffestiniog WW1 Memorial Hospital, Blaenau Ffestiniog (geograph 6220104).jpg\n| image alt   = \n| Caption     = Ffestiniog Memorial Hospital\n| map_type    = Wales Gwynedd \n| map_caption = Shown in Gwynedd\n| Logo        = <!-- Please conform to copyright -->\n| Logo Size   = <!-- Use to limit the logo size -->\n| Location    = [[Blaenau Ffestiniog]]\n| Region      = [[Gwynedd]]\n| State       = <!-- optional UK: England, Wales, Scotland, Northern Ireland. US: The US State - NB autolinked -->\n| Country     = Wales\n| Coordinates = {{coord|52.9916|-3.9350|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| Address     = <!-- Address of main building -->\n| HealthCare  = [[NHS Wales]]\n| Funding     = <!-- Non-profit, For-profit, Government, Public - will generate linka -->\n| Type        = Community\n| Speciality  = \n| Standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency   = \n| Helipad     = \n| Affiliation = <!-- 'None' or Medical School and university affiliations (medical or paramedical) -->\n| Patron      = <!-- 'None' or the individual who acts as the hospital patron -->\n| Network     = <!-- Hospital network, non-owner -->\n| Beds        = \n| Founded     = 1927\n| Closed      = \n| Website     = \n| Wiki-Links  = <!-- Creates \"\"See also\" field -->\n}}\n'''Ffestiniog Memorial Hospital''' ({{lang-cy|Ysbyty Coffa Ffestiniog}}) is a health facility in [[Blaenau Ffestiniog]], [[Gwynedd]], [[Wales]]. It is managed by the [[Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board]].\n\n==History==\nThe facility, which was designed by [[Clough Williams-Ellis]], was officially opened by Colonel [[David Davies, 1st Baron Davies|David Davies]] MP as the Festiniog and District Heroes Memorial Hospital in 1927.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://player.bfi.org.uk/free/film/watch-opening-ceremony-the-festiniog-district-heroes-memorial-hospital-1927-online|title=Opening Ceremony - the Festiniog & District Heroes Memorial Hospital|publisher=British Film Institute|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> It was intended to commemorate local soldiers who had died in the [[World War I|First World War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iwm.org.uk/memorials/item/memorial/24426|title=Ffestiniog Memorial Hospital|publisher=Imperial war Museum|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> After joining the [[National Health Service]] in 1948, it developed as a community hospital but, after inpatient services transferred to [[Ysbyty Alltwen]] in [[Tremadog]], it closed to inpatients in March 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/local-news/no-beds-plan-blaenau-ffestiniog-2041998|title=No beds plan for Blaenau Ffestiniog Memorial Hospital|date=14 February 2012|publisher=Wales Online|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/blaenau-memorial-hospital-closes-doors-2637960|title=Blaenau Memorial Hospital closes its doors|date=28 March 2013|publisher=Daily Post|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> It then re-opened as the Canolfan Goffa Ffestiniog (English: ''Ffestiniog Memorial Centre'') in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypost.co.uk/news/north-wales-news/new-blaenau-ffestiniog-health-centre-13911981|title=New \u00a33.9m health centre opens its doors|date=17 November 2017|publisher=Daily Post|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in Gwynedd]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1927]]\n[[Category:1927 establishments in Wales]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1927]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in Wales]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ffestiniog_Memorial_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Ferryfield House", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n<!-- All parameters and comments should be left intact for future editors -->\n<!-- All parameters are optional, but please copy the entire template -->\n<!-- Full documentation: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_hospital -->\n| name        = Ferryfield House\n| org/group   = [[NHS Lothian]]\n| logo        = <!-- please conform to copyright -->\n| logo_size   = <!-- logo size or width in pixels -->\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| alt         = <!-- alternative text for image, see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption     = \n| map_type    = Scotland Edinburgh\n| relief      = <!-- any non-blank value (yes, 1, etc.) will cause the template to display a relief map image, where available -->\n| map_size    = <!-- map size or width in pixels (do not include \"px\"); default is 225 -->\n| map_alt     = <!-- alternative text for map image, see WP:ALT for details -->\n| map_caption = Shown in Edinburgh\n| latitude    = <!-- to display coordinates (or: latd / latm / lats / latNS); required if using map_type -->\n| longitude   = <!-- to display coordinates (or: longd / longm / longs / longEW); required if using map_type -->\n| location    = [[Pilton, Edinburgh]]\n| region      = \n| state       = \n| country     = Scotland\n| coordinates = {{coord|55|58|13|N|3|13|48|W|region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| healthcare  = NHS\n| funding     = Public\n| type        = Community Hospital\n| affiliation = <!-- medical school / university affiliations (medical or paramedical) -->\n| patron      = <!-- the individual who acts as the hospital patron -->\n| network     = <!-- hospital network, non-owner -->\n| standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| emergency   = No\n| helipad     = No\n| beds        = 60\n| speciality  = <!-- if devoted to a speciality (i.e. not a broad spectrum); ONLY displayed if type=Specialist or type=Teaching -->\n| founded     = October 1996\n| closed      = <!-- if defunct, please also add to Category:Defunct hospitals -->\n| demolished  = <!-- if demolished at a different time from closure -->\n| website     = <!-- use {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| other_links = <!-- link(s) to related articles -->\n| module      = <!-- or 'embedded' or 'nrhp' -->\n}}\n'''Ferryfield House''' is a [[community hospital]] in [[Pilton, Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]].  It is managed by [[NHS Lothian]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhslothian.scot.nhs.uk/GoingToHospital/Locations/Pages/FerryfieldHouse.aspx |title=Ferryfield House |publisher=[[NHS Lothian]] |date=1 June 2011 |accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe hospital has its origins in the Leith Public Hospital which was designed by James Simpson and opened in 1896.<ref name=canmore>{{cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/302218/edinburgh-100-pilton-drive-ferryfield-house|title=Ferryfield House|publisher=Canmore|accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref> The facility was subsequently renamed the Northern General Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkerhealthcare.co.uk/care-facilities/ferryfield-house-edinburgh/|title=Ferrybridge House, Edinburgh|publisher=Walker Healthcare|accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nA new hospital, which was commissioned to replace the Northern General Hospital, was procured under a [[Private Finance Initiative]] ('PFI') contract in 1993, the first hospital project in Scotland to use this form of procurement.<ref name=10yAnniversary>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/tenth-anniversary-celebrations-for-elderly-care-home-1-1001895 |title=Tenth anniversary celebrations for elderly care home |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=13 October 2006 |accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref> The site had previously been part of [[City Park, Edinburgh|City Park]], the first home of [[Livingston F.C.]]<ref name=canmore/> The new hospital was built by James Walker (Leith) Limited<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199899/cmhansrd/vo990322/text/90322w20.htm|title=Private Finance Initiative|publisher=Hansard|date=22 March 1999|accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref> at a cost of \u00a32 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199900/cmselect/cmtreasy/uc147/uc14702.htm|title=Memorandum by HM Treasury|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref> and opened in October 1996.<ref name=10yAnniversary/>\n\n==Services==\nFerryfield House is a 60-bed unit that specialises in short-term and respite care.<ref name=10yAnniversary/> There are two wards, with one used to treat patients with \"dementia and challenging behaviour\" and the other for the frail and elderly.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vulnerable dementia patient attacked in hospital|url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/health/vulnerable-dementia-patient-attacked-in-hospital-1-3033433|accessdate=26 December 2014|publisher=Edinburgh News|date=7 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:NHS Scotland hospitals]]\n[[Category:NHS Lothian]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Edinburgh]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-org-stub}}\n{{Scotland-struct-stub}}\n{{Edinburgh-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n<!-- All parameters and comments should be left intact for future editors -->\n<!-- All parameters are optional, but please copy the entire template -->\n<!-- Full documentation: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_hospital -->\n| name        = Ferryfield House\n| org/group   = [[NHS Lothian]]\n| logo        = <!-- please conform to copyright -->\n| logo_size   = <!-- logo size or width in pixels -->\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| alt         = <!-- alternative text for image, see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption     = \n| map_type    = Scotland Edinburgh\n| relief      = <!-- any non-blank value (yes, 1, etc.) will cause the template to display a relief map image, where available -->\n| map_size    = <!-- map size or width in pixels (do not include \"px\"); default is 225 -->\n| map_alt     = <!-- alternative text for map image, see WP:ALT for details -->\n| map_caption = Shown in Edinburgh\n| latitude    = <!-- to display coordinates (or: latd / latm / lats / latNS); required if using map_type -->\n| longitude   = <!-- to display coordinates (or: longd / longm / longs / longEW); required if using map_type -->\n| location    = [[Pilton, Edinburgh]]\n| region      = \n| state       = \n| country     = Scotland\n| coordinates = {{coord|55|58|13|N|3|13|48|W|region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| healthcare  = NHS\n| funding     = Public\n| type        = Community Hospital\n| affiliation = <!-- medical school / university affiliations (medical or paramedical) -->\n| patron      = <!-- the individual who acts as the hospital patron -->\n| network     = <!-- hospital network, non-owner -->\n| standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| emergency   = No\n| helipad     = No\n| beds        = 60\n| speciality  = <!-- if devoted to a speciality (i.e. not a broad spectrum); ONLY displayed if type=Specialist or type=Teaching -->\n| founded     = October 1996\n| closed      = <!-- if defunct, please also add to Category:Defunct hospitals -->\n| demolished  = <!-- if demolished at a different time from closure -->\n| website     = <!-- use {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| other_links = <!-- link(s) to related articles -->\n| module      = <!-- or 'embedded' or 'nrhp' -->\n}}\n'''Ferryfield House''' is a [[community hospital]] in [[Pilton, Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]].  It is managed by [[NHS Lothian]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhslothian.scot.nhs.uk/GoingToHospital/Locations/Pages/FerryfieldHouse.aspx |title=Ferryfield House |publisher=[[NHS Lothian]] |date=1 June 2011 |accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe hospital has its origins in the Leith Public Hospital which was designed by James Simpson and opened in 1896.<ref name=canmore>{{cite web|url=https://canmore.org.uk/site/302218/edinburgh-100-pilton-drive-ferryfield-house|title=Ferryfield House|publisher=Canmore|accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref> The facility was subsequently renamed the Northern General Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkerhealthcare.co.uk/care-facilities/ferryfield-house-edinburgh/|title=Ferrybridge House, Edinburgh|publisher=Walker Healthcare|accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nA new hospital, which was commissioned to replace the Northern General Hospital, was procured under a [[Private Finance Initiative]] ('PFI') contract in 1993, the first hospital project in Scotland to use this form of procurement.<ref name=10yAnniversary>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/tenth-anniversary-celebrations-for-elderly-care-home-1-1001895 |title=Tenth anniversary celebrations for elderly care home |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=13 October 2006 |accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref> The site had previously been part of [[City Park, Edinburgh|City Park]], the first home of [[Livingston F.C.]]<ref name=canmore/> The new hospital was built by James Walker (Leith) Limited<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199899/cmhansrd/vo990322/text/90322w20.htm|title=Private Finance Initiative|publisher=Hansard|date=22 March 1999|accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref> at a cost of \u00a32 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199900/cmselect/cmtreasy/uc147/uc14702.htm|title=Memorandum by HM Treasury|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=28 December 2018}}</ref> and opened in October 1996.<ref name=10yAnniversary/>\n\n==Services==\nFerryfield House is a 60-bed unit that specialises in short-term and respite care.<ref name=10yAnniversary/> There are two wards, with one used to treat patients with \"dementia and challenging behaviour\" and the other for the frail and elderly.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vulnerable dementia patient attacked in hospital|url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/health/vulnerable-dementia-patient-attacked-in-hospital-1-3033433|accessdate=26 December 2014|publisher=Edinburgh News|date=7 August 2013}}</ref> \n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:NHS Scotland hospitals]]\n[[Category:NHS Lothian]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Edinburgh]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-org-stub}}\n{{Scotland-struct-stub}}\n{{Edinburgh-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ferryfield_House"}
